{[%evp 0,48,39,18,53,53,83,17,-3,-17,-17,-17,28,2,39,-26,-26,-32,-6,-2,8,8,-3,11,54,57,57,24,100,87,92,-25,-59,-15,-15,-15,-9,32,38,38,23,23,46,29,49,24,19,17,31,25,23]} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. f3 {The so-called Fantasy Variation - this quite romantic branch is lately gaining in popularity.} (3. Bd3 {contains a surprising idea to hinder the natural development of Bc8 -} dxe4 4. Bxe4 Nf6 5. Bf3 {looks bizarre, but Black should not relax so early:} Nbd7 {, in combination with fianchettoeing the other bishop, is a reliable way to point at the artificial position of Bf3, for example} (5... Bf5 6. g4 $5 Be6 (6... Bg6 7. h4 $36 {is White's hidden point}) 7. g5 Nd5 8. Ne2 $13) 6. Bf4 Qa5+ $5 (6... Qb6 7. Nc3 g6 8. Nge2 Bg7 9. O-O O-O 10. a4 a5 11. Be3 Qb4 $5) 7. Qd2 Qxd2+ 8. Nxd2 Nd5 9. Bg3 h5 $5 10. h4 g6 $132) 3... dxe4 $5 {3...e6 has been my choice for long, but now I prefer to stick to the Black's most straightforward option.} 4. fxe4 e5 5. Nf3 Bg4 6. c3 {The most flexible continuation, White is not defining the position of Bf1 yet.} (6. Bc4 {looks tempting, but it has a lot of cons as well, for instance, White's center remains vulnerable and requires protection after} Nd7 $1 {, for example:} 7. h3 (7. O-O Ngf6 8. c3 (8. dxe5 Qb6+ 9. Kh1 Nxe5 $132) 8... Bd6 9. Bg5 {The most challenging idea. Before putting the bishop on e3, White wants to provoke the weakening ...h7-h6.} ({Dubious but popular is} 9. Qb3 $6 {In this case, Black is always ready to sacrifice the b7-pawn by means of} O-O 10. Qxb7 Bxf3 {Regardless of how White recaptures on f3, Black enjoys a fantastic compensation.} 11. Rxf3 {The most natural.} ({The alternative is} 11. gxf3 Rb8 12. Qxc6 {This position occurred in the game 0-1 (31) Mendez Machado, A (1962) -Ansh, M (2178) Chess.com INT 2023. At this point, Black could have played} Rb6 13. Qa4 exd4 14. cxd4 Bxh2+ $1 15. Kxh2 Nh5 $19 {with a winning attack.}) 11... exd4 12. cxd4 Ng4 13. h3 Nc5 $1 14. Qxc6 {1-0 (49) Ribeiro,G (2013)-Karsay,P  (2319) Maia 2023 Now, after the precise} Bh2+ $1 15. Kh1 Qxd4 $19 {, White could have resigned.}) 9... h6 $1 10. Be3 ({Less precise is} 10. Bh4 {when after} g5 11. Bg3 Qe7 12. Nbd2 O-O-O $15 {Black is already slightly better.}) 10... O-O (10... Bh5 $5 11. Qe1 Ng4 $132) 11. Nbd2 Bh5 12. Kh1 Re8 13. Qc2 {Borisek - Schandorff, EU-chT (Men), Novi Sad, 2009, when Black can continue in the spirit of the game Vodicka - Ragnarsson, which will be examined a bit later, namely} a6 $5 14. a4 b5 15. Bd3 Rb8 $132) (7. c3 Bd6 8. O-O ({Note that in case of} 8. Qb3 Qe7 9. Qxb7 Rb8 10. Qxc6 Bxf3 11. gxf3 Ngf6 $44 {Black enjoys a fantastic compensation for the pawn in view of White's vulnerable king.}) 8... Ngf6 {leads to transposition.}) 7... Bxf3 8. Qxf3 Qh4+ $5 9. g3 Qf6 10. O-O Qxf3 11. Rxf3 Ngf6 12. c3 Bd6 $132) (6. Nbd2 $5 {sharp attempt which is almost undiscovered. Black has} exd4 {Taking up the gauntlet and not without a reason:} (6... Nd7 $5 {is also possible, most likely transposing to one of the lines below or another.} 7. c3 ({for} 7. Bd3 exd4 {see 6...exd4 7. Bd3 below}) 7... Ngf6 $5 (7... Bd6 8. Nc4 Bc7 9. Be2 $36 {T. Beerdsen - G. Bollen, Dieren, 2023}) 8. Be2 {transposes to the leading line}) 7. Bc4 (7. Bd3 Nd7 8. O-O Ne5 $1 {(we are still going to see more of this motif)} 9. Qe1 Nxd3 10. cxd3 Be6 11. Nb3 (11. Qg3 h6 $132) 11... c5 12. Ng5 Qd7 $132) 7... Nd7 8. O-O Ne5 $1 {Here it is again - Nd2 has temporarily blocked Bc1 and, by making use of this drawback Black forces some exchanges in order to release the tension.} 9. Bb3 Bd6 10. Qe1 Bxf3 11. Nxf3 Nf6 12. Nxd4 (12. Kh1 Bc7 $5 13. Qb4 Qd7 $132) 12... Bc5 13. c3 O-O 14. Bg5 (14. Be3 Nfg4 $132) 14... Bxd4+ 15. cxd4 Qxd4+ 16. Kh1 Ng6 $5 $132) (6. dxe5 Nd7 $5 7. Be3 Qc7 8. Bd4 Ne7 $132) 6... Nd7 7. Be2 $5 {One of the popular locations for Bf1.} ({Essential is} 7. Bc4 Bd6 8. Qb3 (8. O-O Ngf6 {transposes to 6.Bc4 Nd7 7.0-0 Ngf6 8.c3}) 8... Qe7 {with plenty of counterplay after} 9. Qxb7 Rb8 10. Qxc6 Bxf3 $1 11. gxf3 Ngf6 $36) (7. Bd3 {is the other main White's option, when} Ngf6 8. O-O Bd6 {is critical:} 9. Nbd2 (9. Na3 $5 {can complicate the position even more, e.g.} Bxa3 10. bxa3 O-O 11. Rb1 (11. Bg5 Re8 12. Rb1 b5 $132 {may transpose to one of the lines below}) 11... b5 $5 {and now:} 12. a4 (12. Qe1 $5 Bxf3 13. Rxf3 Re8 14. Bg5 h6 (14... exd4 $5 15. cxd4 Qb6 16. Be3 Nxe4 17. d5 Qc7 $1 18. dxc6 Ndf6 $132) 15. Bh4 Qb6 16. Qg3 Re6 $132) 12... a6 13. Qe1 Bxf3 14. Rxf3 Re8 15. Bg5 (15. Rg3 Nf8 $132) (15. h3 Qe7 $132) 15... exd4 $1 16. cxd4 Qb6 $1 17. Be3 Nxe4 $5 18. d5 c5 19. axb5 Qg6 $1 $132 {and the threat 20....Ne5 does not leave any time for White to capture the a6-pawn}) (9. a4 Bc7 $5 10. h3 (10. Na3 {seems consequent, but Black has the adequate reaction} exd4 11. cxd4 Nf8 $1 12. Nc2 Ne6 13. e5 Nd5 $132) 10... Bh5 11. Be3 O-O 12. Nbd2 {Anticipating .... Re8 / \exd4, but now Black succeeds again to exert pressure on the other central pawn by means of the creative} Nc5 $5 13. Bc2 exd4 14. cxd4 Ne6 $132) (9. h3 {has been tested at the highest level, but its merits are arguable -} Bxf3 $5 (9... Bh5 $5) 10. Qxf3 O-O 11. Nd2 exd4 12. cxd4 c5 13. Nc4 cxd4 14. Qf5 g6 (14... Qe7 $5) 15. Qg5 $6 (15. Qf3 Nh5 $132) 15... Be7 $1 $17 {Caruana - Keymer, Titled Tuesday 26th Apr, 2022}) (9. Kh1 O-O 10. Bg5 (10. Nbd2 b5 $1 $132) 10... h6 11. Bh4 c5 $5 ({a direct attempt at clarifying the central structure; much more restrained is} 11... Qc7 12. Nbd2 b5 13. Rc1 a6 14. a4 {Erigaisi - Salem, Sigeman & Co, Malmo, 2022, after the natural} Rfe8 15. Qe1 {and the typical bishop transfer} Bh5 $1 16. Bb1 Bg6 $132 {Black is pretty solid}) 12. d5 g5 13. Bf2 (13. Bg3 c4 14. Bc2 b5 15. Nbd2 Qc7 16. a4 a6 17. Qe1 Bh5 (17... Kg7 18. Nh4 $5 gxh4 19. Bxh4 $44) 18. h4 Kg7 $1 19. hxg5 (19. axb5 axb5 20. Rxa8 Rxa8 21. hxg5 hxg5 22. Nxg5 Rh8 $44) 19... hxg5 20. Nxg5 Rh8 $44) 13... c4 $1 {Here too, this is the key move otherwise, Black's position will be very scary.} 14. Bc2 Bh5 15. Qe1 (15. Bg1 b5 16. b3 Bg6 17. Nbd2 Rc8 $132) 15... Bxf3 16. gxf3 {Z. Amanov - D. Kovalev, Alushta, 2009, when a queenside expansion by} b5 $1 17. b3 Qc7 $132 {is the logical way to proceed}) 9... b5 $1 {A resolute measure against 10.Nc4.} 10. a4 a6 11. h3 Bh5 $1 12. g4 Bg6 13. Nh4 O-O 14. Nxg6 hxg6 15. Nf3 Qb6 (15... Rb8 $5) 16. Kg2 Rad8 17. Qb3 Bb8 18. axb5 axb5 19. Bg5 {M. Vodicka - J. Ragnarsson, EU-ch, 2021,} Qc7 $5 $132) (7. h3 Bxf3 $5 8. Qxf3 Ngf6 $132) 7... Ngf6 8. Nbd2 exd4 $1 ({Less principled is} 8... Bd6 9. Nc4 Bc7 10. Ncxe5 Nxe5 11. Nxe5 Be6 12. Bf4 Nxe4 13. O-O O-O 14. Bd3 $14 {with rich play in the spirit of the King's gambit, Xu - Kushagra, Sunway Formentera, 2023, which can definitely be to White's taste.}) 9. cxd4 Bb4 $1 10. O-O O-O 11. Qc2 $1 {The most consistent continuation - White keeps the tension and prepares to execute the push e4-e5 under the best circumstances.} (11. e5 Nd5 12. Nc4 f6 $5 (12... N7b6 $5 13. Kh1 Bh5 $13) 13. Qb3 Be7 14. Qxb7 (14. Ne3 Be6 15. Qxb7 Nb4 $11 {is about to end in repetition, so is in the text}) 14... Nb4 $1 $11) (11. h3 Bh5 12. e5 Nd5 13. Nc4 {and, even though Black can once again go for the central break 13...f6, regarding the new location of Bh5, he might prefer the cautious} Be7 $5 $132) 11... Bh5 $1 {Once again this typical manoeuvre is very helpful.} 12. Bd3 {This may lead to Erigaisi-Gukesh, see below, but this move order is slightly more flexible in my opinion.} (12. Kh1 Re8 $1 (12... Bg6 $2 {is premature in the view of} 13. Nh4 $16 {, given the sample line} Bxd2 14. Nxg6 Bxc1 15. Nxf8 {, when Black is lacking a check from e3 and will remain an exchange down}) 13. e5 Bg6 14. Qb3 Nd5 15. Bd3 Nf8 16. Bxg6 fxg6 $1 {An instructive moment, whilst avoiding possible trouble along a semi-open h-file, Nf8 should not be deflected from its appointment - the perfect blockading e6-square.} 17. Ne4 Qb6 18. Qd3 Ne6 $132) (12. a3 Bxd2 13. Bxd2 Re8 $6 (13... Bg6 $1 {is the precise move with transposition to the leading line after} 14. Bd3) 14. e5 Nd5 15. Bd3 $14 {Erigaisi - Gukesh, Airthings Masters, rapid, 2023.}) 12... Bg6 $1 {now White has various attempts to fortify the center but Black has always enough to counterattack} 13. a3 (13. Nh4 {provides Black with two very promisng options against the undefended d4-pawn:} Bxd2 $1 {(here Black must not worry about 14.Nxg6)} ({Black can altogether ignore 14. Nxg6 and rely on the central counterstrike} 13... c5 $5 {, as witnessed by} 14. Nxg6 hxg6 15. e5 Ng4 16. Rf4 $1 Ne3 17. Qb3 {and the key resource} Nxg2 $1 $132 18. Rxf7 Rxf7 {, when Black is opposing} 19. Bxg6 {with the brilliant} Nxe5 $1 20. dxe5 Qd4+ 21. Kxg2 Qg4+ 22. Qg3 Qe2+ 23. Kg1 ({it is remarkable that} 23. Kh3 $2 {fails to} Rf2 $1) 23... Raf8 $1 ({a reasonable try for more; Black, if he wishes so, can just repeat -} 23... Qd1+ 24. Kg2 Qe2+ $11) 24. Bxf7+ Rxf7 25. e6 Rf6 26. e7 {and here comes the next beautiful point} c4 $1 {with multiple threats}) 14. Bxd2 Qb6 15. Bc3 $1 c5 $1 {(the final well-timed shot)} 16. Qa4 $1 cxd4 17. Bxd4 Qd6 $1 18. Rad1 Ng4 19. Nf3 Nde5 $132) (13. Re1 Re8 14. a3 Bxd2 15. Bxd2 Nf8 $1 ({White has prepared to meet the immediate} 15... c5 $2 {with} 16. e5 {, but Black can delay the strike at this central pawn till the most appropriate moment}) 16. Bc3 Qb6 17. Rad1 c5 $132) 13... Bxd2 14. Bxd2 {White has almost managed to overprotect the central pair, but the well-timed counterstrike} c5 $1 {is supposed to shake this optical preponderance.} ({On the contrary, half-measures like} 14... Re8 15. Rae1 Nf8 $6 {will just enable the opponent to reinforce the center, for instance} 16. Bc3 $36) 15. Rae1 $1 ({Simply bad for White is} 15. dxc5 $2 Nxc5 $17) ({An important justification of black's operation is revealed by} 15. e5 Nxe5 $1 16. Bxg6 Nxf3+ 17. Rxf3 hxg6 18. dxc5 Rc8 ({the most natural continuation; good enough is} 18... Qd5 19. Rd3 Qh5 $132 {as well}) 19. Rd1 b6 20. Bc3 Qc7 21. Bxf6 gxf6 22. Rxf6 Qxc5+ 23. Qxc5 Rxc5 24. Rd7 Kg7 25. Rf1 a5 {with complete equality}) ({Black is able to neutralize} 15. Bg5 {with the help of the consequent and strong} Rc8 $1 {, based on the common tactical nuance} 16. e5 Nxe5 $1 17. Bxg6 $140 Nxf3+ 18. Rxf3 hxg6 19. dxc5 Qd4+ {with pressure along the open central files after} 20. Be3 Qe5 21. Rc1 Rfe8 $132) (15. d5 c4 $1 16. Qxc4 Qb6+ {and Black is about to seize the initiative, in case of} 17. Kh1 Rfc8 18. Qb4 {the internediate} Nc5 {is probably even stronger than winning the pawn back at once.}) 15... cxd4 16. e5 Rc8 $1 17. Qb1 Bxd3 18. Qxd3 Nc5 19. Qxd4 (19. Qf5 Qd7 $1 $11) 19... Qxd4+ 20. Nxd4 Nd5 {After all the simplifications Black should equalize easily.} 21. Nf5 Rc7 22. Rc1 b6 $5 23. Rfd1 Ne7 24. Nd6 Ng6 $132 *

