{[%evp 0,28,25,16,77,69,56,42,54,25,34,24,23,21,13,21,21,25,2,-12,23,8,13,15,7,15,10,13,12,5,21]} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 {There are various alternatives to the main line 4.Bd3, most of the ensuing positions can occur via the extremely popular London system as well..} 4. c3 (4. Bf4 Nc6 {is exactly on the verge of these two openings:} 5. c3 (5. Nf3 {leads to a favourable version for Black of the line with 4.Bd3 and 5.Nf3 after} Bg4 (5... Bf5 $5) 6. c3 e6 7. Qb3 (7. Bd3 Bd6 8. Bxd6 Qxd6 9. O-O Nf6 {Black is flexible and can develop the knight on e7 as well.} 10. Nbd2) 7... Qd7 8. Nbd2 f6 $1 {A key move in this setup.} 9. Bd3 $6 (9. Bg3 $142 Nge7 $132) 9... g5 10. Bg3 Bf5 $1 {One more splendid idea!} 11. Bxf5 exf5 12. h4 $140 f4 13. Bh2 g4 (13... h6 $5 $15) 14. Ng1 g3 $1 15. fxg3 O-O-O $36) 5... Bf5 $1 6. Nd2 (6. Bd3 Bxd3 7. Qxd3 e6 8. Nd2 Bd6 9. Bxd6 Qxd6 10. Ngf3 Nf6 11. O-O O-O 12. Rfe1 Nd7 13. a4 {with typical for the Carlsbad structure tense middlegame struggle, Sadhwani - Murzin, Titled Tuesday 7th Sept, 2021, a possible continuation is} h6 $5 14. a5 a6 15. Nb3 Qc7 16. h3 Rab8 $132) 6... e6 {and now:} 7. Ngf3 {seems harmless, as Black has many decent set-ups:} (7. Qb3 Qd7 8. Ngf3 f6 $1 9. h4 Nh6 $5 {A remarkable opening plan, which is providing Black with good chances to take over the initiative, for example} 10. Be2 (10. Bxh6 gxh6 11. Bb5 a6 $15) 10... Nf7 11. h5 e5 (11... O-O-O $5 $132) 12. dxe5 fxe5 13. Bg3 Bc5 (13... Be7 $132) 14. Qb5 Bb6 15. Rd1 Bc2 16. Rc1 Bf5 17. Rd1 Bc2 18. Rc1 Bf5 {, when} 19. c4 $6 d4 20. c5 {Kamsky - Dreev, Chess.com, rapid, 2022, could be met by} Ba5 21. O-O d3 $15) 7... Bd6 (7... h6 $5 8. Qb3 (8. Bb5 Qb6) 8... Qd7 $132) 8. Bxd6 Qxd6 9. Nh4 (9. a4 Nge7 (9... Nf6 $5) 10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O h6 12. Re1 {Gukesh - Harikrishna, Tata Steel blitz, Kolkata, 2023, when safe enough is} Qc7 13. Bf1 Nc8 $132) (9. Bb5 h6 $5 10. O-O Nge7 11. Re1 O-O 12. Nb3 {So far Tassone - Kazoks, EU-ch 2019, Black could opt for the same plan -} a5 13. a4 Qc7 14. Nc5 Nc8 $1 $132) 9... Nf6 $1 {leads to yet another important structure, which is worth to be understood - as it frequently happens in the Caro-Kann, the kingside pawn majority with doubled f-pawns is yielding Black quite decent play, e.g.} 10. Nxf5 (10. Bb5 O-O 11. O-O Bg4 $132) 10... exf5 11. Bd3 g6 12. O-O O-O 13. Re1 Kg7 14. Nf3 Rfe8 $132) (4. Nf3 Nc6 {presents White with a similar choice:} 5. Bb5 (5. c3 {will very likely transpose to some other line after} Bf5 6. Nh4 (6. Qb3 Qd7) 6... Bd7 7. g3 ({an amusing blunder is} 7. Bf4 $4 e5 $1 $19) (7. Nf3 Bf5 ({is just repeating, while continuing on playing with extra Bd7 on the board after} 7... e6 $5 {also makes a lot of sense})) 7... e5 8. dxe5 Nxe5 9. Nf3 ({notable is also} 9. Bg2 Bb5 $132) 9... Nxf3+ 10. Qxf3 Bc5 11. Nd2 Nf6 $132 {Black is once again very active}) 5... Qa5+ $5 {Forcing the opponent to cover with the knight, when the situation resembles the Ragozin, in which Nc3 (as well as Nc6 in its original form) is often misplaced.} 6. Nc3 Bg4 7. h3 (7. O-O e6 8. Bf4 Nf6 9. h3 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 Be7 $132) 7... Bxf3 8. Qxf3 e6 9. O-O (9. Bf4 Nf6 10. O-O Be7 11. Rfd1 O-O 12. a3 {Niemann - Matlakov, Chess.com, rapid, 2022, when Black is at least equal after} Rac8 13. Bf1 (13. Be3 $6 Ne4 $1) 13... Qd8 $5 $132) (9. a3 Bd6 10. Qg4 Kf8 {Due to his solid center, the loss of castling rights is not a serious concern for Black.} 11. O-O (11. Bf4 Qc7 12. Bxd6+ Qxd6 $132) 11... Nf6 12. Qd1 (12. Qh4 h6 13. Bd3 Qd8 $5 $132) 12... Rc8 13. Be3 {D. Harika - D. Howell, PRO League Prelim, rapid 2023, when} h5 $5 14. Bd3 Bb8 $36 {is worth of try}) 9... Nf6 10. Qg3 $5 {Yet another move in the spirit of the reversed Ragozin, White is hindering the natural development of Be7 by both taking the h2-b8 diagonal under control and keeping an eye on the g7-pawn.} (10. a3 Rc8 $5 11. Be3 ({to} 11. Bf4 {critical is} Qb6 $5) 11... Bd6 12. Bd3 O-O 13. Ne2 Rfe8 14. Rad1 Bb8 $5 $132 {preparing both e6-e5 and building a battery by Qa5-c7}) (10. Be3 Bd6 11. a3 O-O 12. Bd3 Rac8 {is also fine for Black}) 10... a6 $5 (10... Qd8 $5 {is also interesting, having} 11. Re1 Rc8 {in mind}) 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. Rd1 Qd8 13. b3 {Blomqvist - Houska, NOR-chT, 2017, now the subtle} h6 $1 {is a very typical idea of how to get rid of the annoying Qg3, as it will be trapped by Rh7 after an eventual sequence 14....Bd6, when 15. Qxg7?? would be therefore a huge blunder, so} 14. Qf3 Bd6 $132) 4... Bf5 $5 {Black is immediately making use of the absence of Bd3 in order to realize the main goal of the Caro-Kann and solve the problem with the development of its counterpart.} (4... Nf6 {is likely to transpose to our main lines, but there are some of them after} 5. Nf3 {, which I would wish to avoid, such as} Bg4 (5... Nc6 6. Ne5 $5) 6. h3 Bxf3 (6... Bh5 $6 7. Qb3 Qb6 8. g4 Bg6 9. Ne5 $36) 7. Qxf3 $14) 5. Qb3 {If White is planning this sally, then it is advisable to go for it at once.} (5. Nf3 e6 6. Qb3 Qc7 $1 {reveals a drawback of the deferred appearance of the queen on b3, for the d5-pawn does not need protection anymore.} 7. Be2 (7. Nh4 Bg4 8. h3 Bh5 9. g4 Bg6 10. Nxg6 hxg6 $132) 7... Nf6 ({Black should at first bring into play exactly this knight rather than falling into} 7... Nc6 $6 8. Bf4 $1) (7... Bd6 $6 {is also imprecise because of the tricky} 8. Na3 a6 9. Qa4+ $1 $14) 8. Na3 $5 ({here} 8. Bf4 $2 {is running into} Qxf4 9. Qxb7 Qc1+ 10. Bd1 Bd3 $1 11. Qxa8 Bd6 $19 {and White, with his king, stuck in the center, can hardly disentangle}) 8... a6 $5 (8... Be7 $5 9. Ne5 (9. Bf4 $2 Qxf4 10. Qxb7 Bxa3 $19) 9... h6 10. Bf4 Qc8 $132) 9. Bf4 Qc8 {(the refutation of 9.Bf4 from above is not working here because of the hanging a6-pawn after capturing Ra8, which will help her Majesty to be liberated from the corner)} 10. O-O Nc6 11. Nc2 Be7 $132) 5... Qd7 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Nh4 $1 {The best practical chance, Black will be enjoying a very comfortable play with the help of the typical f7-f6 idea, as shown by:} (7. Bb5 f6 $1 8. O-O e6 9. Re1 {F. Svane - D. Andreikin, Titled Tuesday 1st Febr, 2022, when fully playable is} a6 10. Bf1 (10. Bxc6 Qxc6 11. Nh4 Bg4 $15) 10... g5 $1 $15) (7. Ne5 Nxe5 8. dxe5 a6 9. Be3 e6 10. f4 Ne7 11. Nd2 Nc6 $132 {with a good version of the Advanced Variation, H. Metz - M. Bucher, Verbandsliga Sued Baden, 2008}) (7. Bf4 f6 $1 8. h4 Nh6 $1 9. Nbd2 Nf7 10. Bb5 a6 11. Bxc6 {So far B. Korpa - G. Papidakis, GRE-chT, Thessaloniki, 2022, when} bxc6 $1 12. O-O e6 $132 {seems to be the simplest}) 7... Be6 $5 {This retreat seems to be Black's best. I have been trying other moves in online games:} (7... e6 8. Nxf5 exf5 9. Bd3 Nf6 10. O-O Be7 11. Nd2 O-O 12. Nf3 $14 {/=}) (7... g6 $6 8. Nxf5 gxf5 9. Nd2 (9. Bf4 {F. Svane - P. Eljanov, Titled Tuesday 31st May, blitz, 2022, allows} O-O-O 10. Nd2 Qe6+ $132) 9... e6 10. Nf3 Nf6 11. Bf4 $14) 8. Bd3 (8. f4 g6 9. Nd2 Nf6 $132) 8... f6 $1 9. f4 $5 Bf7 10. O-O (10. f5 {looks overoptimistic, for instance} O-O-O 11. O-O g5 $1 12. Nf3 ({it is not recommendable to open files against the own king by} 12. fxg6 $2 hxg6 13. Nxg6 Bxg6 14. Bxg6 e6 $36) 12... Nh6 13. Na3 e5 14. fxe6 Qxe6 15. Bd2 Bg6 $132) 10... e6 11. Nd2 Bd6 12. Qd1 (12. g3 Bh5 $1 13. f5 e5 14. Qxd5 Nge7 15. Qe4 exd4 $36) (12. Ndf3 {is too artificial, after} Nge7 13. Bd2 h6 $1 {White's position is already quite dangerous:} 14. g3 $2 (14. Qc2 Rg8 15. Ng6 (15. Bh7 Rf8 $15) 15... Nxg6 16. Bxg6 O-O-O $132) 14... g5 $1 15. Ng2 {frederiksvane (2865)-eljanov (2862) Live Chess Chess. com 2023, now the easiest way to proceed is} gxf4 16. gxf4 (16. Nxf4 e5 $17) 16... Rg8 $17) 12... Nge7 (12... f5 $5 13. g4 $1 g6 14. Ndf3 Nf6 15. Ne5 Qc7 $132) 13. Qg4 g6 14. Qe2 {Now Black can either castle or keep the king in the center for some time, continuing with, let us say,} h6 $5 {In both cases I like Black's position, although it is complex.} *

