{[%evp 0,46,18,17,60,83,77,58,33,30,30,25,24,25,28,26,36,18,31,14,19,17,13,26,14,15,24,15,11,3,-2,2,7,10,16,21,27,27,10,31,31,31,22,18,20,11,12,14,14]} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nf6 $5 {Not so much time ago this jump was a rare guest in practice, but nowadays it has become almost as popular as the main reply 4...Nc6. The main idea behind it is to prepare Bc8-g4 immediately and fight against the most unpleasant White's setup with c3, Bf4 etc.} ({For instance, after} 4... Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 $1 Bg4 7. Qb3 Qd7 8. Nd2 e6 9. Ngf3 Bd6 10. Bxd6 Qxd6 11. O-O O-O 12. Rfe1 {, supposedly the main line, White is getting the same position we are going to analyze in this Chapter with an extra Qd1-b3, which is of course in his favour.}) 5. Nf3 (5. h3 {is excluding the opportunity for Bc8-g4, but then comes} Nc6 {Now White cannot simultaneously prevent the thrust e7-e5 or the jump Nc6-b4:} 6. c3 (6. Nf3 Nb4 $1 7. Nc3 $5 {A creative way to get a playable position.} (7. Bb5+ Bd7 8. Bxd7+ Qxd7 9. c3 Nc6 {is harmless for Black -} 10. O-O (10. Ne5 Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qe6 $5 $132) 10... e6 11. Bf4 Bd6 $11) 7... e6 $5 {The most precise answer.} (7... g6 8. Ne5 a6 9. O-O Bg7 10. Re1 O-O {Aronian - Keymer, Berlin, FIDE GP, 2022} 11. Bf1 $14) ({besides, Black should not hurry with an exchange, because White has a dangerous plan to castle to the long, e. g.} 7... Nxd3+ 8. Qxd3 e6 9. h4 $5 Bd6 10. h5 h6 11. Ne5 $36) 8. Ne5 (8. O-O Bd6 9. Bg5 O-O 10. Re1 Nxd3 11. Qxd3 Bd7 12. Ne5 Qc7 $5 $132) (8. h4 Bd6 9. h5 {is an interesting thought, but it is hard to believe in it} h6 $15) 8... Bd6 9. Bg5 Qb6 $132) 6... e5 $1 {seems to be the most logical and straightforward way to equality, after} ({In some blitz games I used to play} 6... g6 {, which is solid and playable, but White has a more pleasant game in this typical structure due to the fact the g6-pawn does not generally belong to the traditional set-up.} 7. Nf3 Bf5 8. O-O (8. Be2 $5) (8. Bb5 $5) 8... Bxd3 9. Qxd3 e6 10. Re1 Qc7 11. Bg5 Bg7 (11... Ne4 12. Be3 Bg7 13. Nbd2 Nxd2 14. Qxd2 $14 {Alexakis - Sandalakis, GRE-chT, Nikaia, 2023}) 12. Nbd2 $14 {/=}) 7. dxe5 Nxe5 {White has two main options:} 8. Qe2 {White's main move:} (8. Nf3 Nxd3+ 9. Qxd3 Bd6 10. O-O O-O 11. Bg5 (11. Be3 {is solid, but not dangerous, Black can choose from:} Re8 (11... Be6 $5 12. Nbd2 (12. Bg5 h6 13. Bh4 g5 14. Bg3 Bxg3 15. fxg3 Ne4 16. Nd4 {Antipov - Seo, Titled Tuesday 22nd Dec, 2020, when good is} Qb6 $1 17. Nd2 f5 18. g4 Rae8 19. gxf5 Bxf5 $132) 12... Qd7 13. Rfe1 ({after} 13. Qd4 Rfe8 14. Bf4 {Artemiev - Gunina, Kazan Mayors Cup rapid, 2022, the dark-squared bishop should indeed be preserved -} Bf8 $1 15. Rfe1 Qb5 16. Nb3 a5 $132) 13... Rfe8 14. Nd4 ({in reply to} 14. Rad1 {Artemiev - Rozum, RUS-ch Higher League, Obninsk, 2022, Black can once again concentrate on the e4-forepost by} Bf5 $5 15. Qf1 h6 16. Bd4 Ne4 $36) 14... Bxh3 $1 15. gxh3 Qxh3 16. Qf5 $1 Ng4 $1 (16... Bh2+ $5 17. Kh1 Ng4 18. Nf1 Bg3+ 19. Kg1 $11) 17. Nf1 Re4 $5 18. Qf3 Bh2+ 19. Nxh2 Qxh2+ 20. Kf1 f5 $1 $44) (11... a5 $5 {Nobody played this move yet, but it seems like quite an interesting way to bring Ra8 into play, e.g.} 12. Nbd2 Ra6 $5 13. Rfe1 h6 $132) 12. Nbd2 h6 $1 ({there are some problems with the isolated pawn to be solved after} 12... Ne4 13. Rfd1 Bf5 14. Nf1 $1 $14 {/=, so Black keeps Nf6 at place with an original idea about it in mind}) 13. Rad1 Qc7 14. Rfe1 Bd7 15. Bd4 Nh5 $1 $132) 11... h6 12. Bh4 ({accepting the pawn with} 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. Qxd5 (13. Nbd2 Rd8 $132) {looks more dangerous for White, for example} 13... Rd8 14. Qh5 g6 (14... b5 $5 $44) (14... Bf5 $5 $44) 15. Qxh6 Bf4 16. Qh4 g5 17. Qh5 Kg7 18. Nd4 {and, even though Qh5 will escape, the h-file will be inevitably opened:} g4 (18... Rh8 19. Qe2 Bxh3 (19... g4) 20. gxh3 Rxh3 {and after doubling the rooks Black will practically have the draw in his pocket}) 19. g3 Rh8 20. Qd5 Rxh3 21. gxf4 Qxf4 22. Re1 Qh2+ 23. Kf1 g3 {forces White to force a perpetual, e.g.} 24. Qe5+ Kg8 25. Qe8+ Kg7 $11) 12... g5 $5 {The most straightforward way to get a decent position.} 13. Bg3 Bxg3 14. fxg3 g4 $1 15. hxg4 Nxg4 {and after} 16. Nbd2 {the mutual weaknesses are counterbalancing each other:} Re8 $5 $132 (16... Qb6+ $5 17. Nd4 ({the note from above is valid for the queenless endgame after} 17. Qd4 Qxd4+ 18. Nxd4 Bd7 $132 {, see the featured game below for more details}) 17... Bd7 18. Rf4 Rae8 $132) 17. Rae1 Qb6+ 18. Qd4 Qxd4+ 19. Nxd4 Bd7 20. N2f3 Rxe1 (20... a5 $5 $132) 21. Rxe1 Re8 22. Rxe8+ Bxe8 $11 {and the verdict remained unchanged in M. Kobalia - R. Svane, Titled Tuesday 14th Jun, 2022}) (8. Bb5+ $6 Bd7 9. Bxd7+ Qxd7 10. Nf3 Nxf3+ 11. Qxf3 Qe6+ 12. Be3 Bc5 $15) 8... Ne4 $5 {An ambitious idea to take advantage of the insertions on moves 4 and 5 in comparison to 4... .Nc6 5.c3 e5.} (8... Qe7 {Keymer's line, which is the sharper (not necessarily in my opinion) of the two options.} 9. Bc2 b6 {The trendy continuation and now:} 10. Na3 ({of course,} 10. Be3 $6 {is just inviting} Nc4) (10. Bf4 Nc4 11. b3 Nd6 12. Bd3 $1 (12. Nf3 $6 Ba6 $15 {will entirely justify Black's plan}) 12... Bb7 $5 (12... Bf5 $11) 13. Nf3 Qxe2+ 14. Kxe2 Nfe4 $132) 10... Ba6 11. Nb5 {is White's critical reaction:} Rc8 {A crazy position has arisen White has a wide choice.} (11... O-O-O 12. a4 d4 ({the textmove has led to an entertaining queen sacrifice; Black has decent alternatives -} 12... Kb7 {has been played in Antipov: Keymer, Chessable Masters, rapid, 2023,} 13. Bg5 d4 14. Be4+ Kb8 15. Nf3 $36) (12... Re8 13. Kf1 Ne4 {is also possible, after} 14. Nd6+ Qxd6 15. Qxa6+ Kb8 16. a5 Qf6 17. Bxe4 dxe4 {Black is ready to exert more pressure on the f2-pawn}) 13. cxd4 Rxd4 14. Nxd4 Bxe2 15. Ngxe2 $36 {M. Antipov - G. Vazquez, Saint Louis, rapid, 2022}) 12. Bg5 (12. f4 Nc4 13. Nxa7 Rc5 14. Qxe7+ Bxe7 15. Nf3 O-O 16. Nd4 Ne4 $44) (12. a4 {is probably a waste of time, Black can fight for the advantage by means of} d4 $1 13. Bf4 $140 dxc3 14. Bxe5 cxb2 15. Rb1 Rxc2 16. Qxc2 Qxe5+ 17. Ne2 Bb4+ $36) 12... Nc4 13. Nxa7 (13. a4 d4 14. Nxd4 Nxb2 15. Bxf6 gxf6 $132) 13... Qxe2+ 14. Nxe2 Ra8 15. Ba4+ Kd8 16. Bxf6+ gxf6 17. Nc6+ Kc7 18. Ncd4 Nxb2 $132) 9. Bb5+ (9. Bxe4 dxe4 10. Qxe4 Bd6 $44 {is based on} 11. Nf3 O-O $1 {and now:} 12. O-O (12. Nxe5 Bxe5 13. O-O Re8 {and here} 14. Qf3 {M. Socko - P. Shuvalova, Sharjah Cup Final (Women), rapid, 2021,} ({White should have better looked at keeping the balance by returning the pawn -} 14. Bf4 $1 Bxc3 15. Qc2 $8 Bf6 16. Nc3 $11) {could backfire after the vigorous} 14... Bd7 $1 $17 15. Qxb7 $140 Rb8 {with full mobilization and rich play for the invested pawns}) 12... Re8 13. Rd1 Qf6 {Black has again enough compensation at least}) 9... Bd7 10. Nf3 (10. Bxd7+ Qxd7 11. Nf3 ({it is essential that} 11. f3 $2 {is running into} O-O-O 12. fxe4 dxe4 13. Be3 Nd3+ 14. Kf1 Qf5+ $19 {Lahav - Gunina, Online Olymp Div Top-C, rapid, 2021}) 11... Ng6 $5 12. Be3 (12. O-O Bc5 13. Nbd2 Nf4 14. Qd1 Nd3 $132) 12... Bd6 {with a nice version of the French -} 13. Nbd2 O-O 14. O-O Rfe8 $132) 10... Bxb5 (10... Ng6 $5 {is an invitation to transpose to the line from above, but White can pose some problems with} 11. Nd4 $5 (11. O-O Bc5 12. Be3 Bxe3 13. Bxd7+ Qxd7 14. Qxe3 O-O $132 {So - Firouzja, Speed Chess, blitz, 2023}) 11... Be7 12. Nd2 Nc5 13. N2f3 $14 {/=}) 11. Qxb5+ Qd7 {The most precise way to equalize in my opinion, for example} 12. Qxd7+ ({we have already seen of} 12. Qe2 Ng6 13. Be3 Bd6 14. Nbd2 O-O {, castling to the other side} 15. O-O-O {seems to be a risky affair, for instance} Rae8 16. Nxe4 dxe4 17. Nd4 Nf4 $13) 12... Nxd7 13. O-O ({more cautious is} 13. Be3 Bc5 14. Bd4 O-O 15. O-O Rac8 $132) 13... Bc5 {Black is quite active and this is entirely compensating the isolated central pawn:} 14. Nbd2 (14. Bf4 Nf8 $1 ({this subtle manoeuvre for establishing control over the ket d4-square is much more flexible than} 14... O-O 15. Nbd2 Ndf6 16. Nb3 $14 {S. Sargsyan - A. Donchenko, Jermuk Avagyan Memorial, 2022}) 15. Nbd2 Ne6 16. Bh2 Nxd2 17. Nxd2 d4 $11) 14... f6 $5 15. Nb3 (15. Nxe4 dxe4 16. Re1 f5 $132) 15... Bb6 16. a4 Ndc5 17. Nbd4 Nd3 18. a5 Bc5 $132) (5. Bf4 {Here Black has a decent choice between two good options:} Bg4 $5 {is simpler and most likely transposes to the main line of this Chapter, for instance} (5... Qb6 {is the sharper of the two, White is about to lose a pawn, but his initiative in return should not be underestimated -} 6. Nc3 (6. b3 $6 Bg4 7. Ne2 Nc6 $15) 6... Bd7 7. Nf3 (7. Rb1 $2 Qxd4 $17) 7... Qxb2 8. Nb5 (8. Ne2 Qb4+ 9. Bd2 Qb6 10. O-O g6 11. Rb1 Qc7 12. Bf4 Qc8 $132) (8. Bd2 Qb6 9. Rb1 Qc7 10. Nb5 Bxb5 11. Bxb5+ Nbd7 12. c4 dxc4 13. O-O a6 14. Qa4 Rc8) 8... Bxb5 9. Rb1 Qc3+ 10. Bd2 Qc8 11. Bxb5+ Nc6 12. c4 $44 {Black is objectively holding, but it looks a bit dangerous for a practical game.} e6 13. Ne5 (13. Qa4 Bd6 14. Bb4 Ne4 15. cxd5 exd5 16. O-O O-O $11) 13... Bd6 14. Rc1 O-O 15. cxd5 Nxd5 16. Nxc6 bxc6 17. Bxc6 {and here comes the saving resource} Ba3 $5 (17... Nb4 18. Be4 Qd7 $11) 18. Rc4 Nb4 $11) 6. Nf3 e6 7. c3 Bd6 8. Bxd6 Qxd6 9. Nbd2 Nc6 10. h3 Bh5 {etc.}) 5... Nc6 6. c3 Bg4 {Now White's main choice is whether to play the typical Bc1-f4 with or without the insertion of h3 and Bh5. There is no big difference in my opinion, but from White's practical point of view it makes sense to deprive the opponent of the extra Bf5 resource until the bishop is still on g4, so} 7. h3 (7. O-O e6 8. Bf4 {This move order provides Black with an extra option like} Ne4 $5 9. Re1 (9. h3 $6 {Kamsky - Salem, Djerba Blitz Masters KO, 2020, may cause trouble after the effective intermezzo} Qf6 $1 10. Bxe4 dxe4 11. Bg3 Bxf3 12. gxf3 exf3 $15) 9... Bd6 10. Bxd6 Nxd6 11. Nbd2 O-O 12. h3 Bf5 13. Bxf5 Nxf5 14. Nb3 Nd6 $132) (7. Bf4 e6 8. Nbd2 (8. Qb3 {is pointless here, since after} Bd6 {the greedy} 9. Qxb7 $6 {is very dangerous for White, as proved by} O-O $1 10. Bg3 (10. Qxc6 $2 Bxf4 11. Nbd2 Rb8 12. Rb1 Qa5 $17) 10... Bxg3 11. hxg3 Qd6 12. Qa6 Rab8 13. Nbd2 {Mazzilli - Pasini, ITA-chTB, Montesilvano, 2022, when Black has a pleasant choice -} Rb6 $5 (13... Rxb2 $5) 14. Qa3 Qxa3 15. bxa3 Bf5 $15) 8... Bd6 (8... Nh5 $5 9. Be3 Nf6 {is curious and can be even considered a silent draw offer}) 9. Bxd6 Qxd6 10. O-O O-O 11. Re1 Rfe8 12. Qc2 (12. Qb3 Qc7 13. a4 (13. h3 Bh5) 13... Bh5 ({according to the modern approach, Black could have preferred} 13... h6 $5 14. Ne5 Bf5 15. Bxf5 exf5 $132) 14. Bb5 {Radjabov - Kuzubov, AI Cup, rapid, 2023, with mutual chances after} a6 15. Bxc6 bxc6 16. Ne5 c5 $132) 12... Rac8 13. a3 Bh5 14. h3 {cf7}) (7. Qb3 $6 {is ill-timed,  and leads simply to inferior reversed Carlsbad after} Qc7 8. Nbd2 e6) 7... Bh5 8. Bf4 e6 9. Nbd2 ({If} 9. O-O {, then there is also} Ne4 $5 10. Re1 $140 Bd6) 9... Bd6 10. Bxd6 Qxd6 11. O-O O-O 12. Re1 (12. Qe2 $5 {is a rather typical manoeuvre - the queen aims at the e3-square.} Nd7 13. Qe3 Rae8 14. Rae1 (14. Qg5 Bxf3 15. Nxf3 e5 $1 $132) (14. Rfe1 f6 $5 15. Nh4 g5 $132) 14... f6 $5 (14... h6 $5 15. Nb3 (15. g4 $6 Bg6 16. Bxg6 fxg6 17. Nh4 e5 $132) 15... Bxf3 16. Qxf3 Re7 17. Re3 Rfe8 18. Rd1 {and, having done all the useful prophylactic moves, Black can turn his attention to the queenside and the usual minority attack -} a6 $5 $132 {etc.}) 15. Nh4 (15. Bc2 Re7 $132) 15... g5 16. g4 $1 Bf7 17. Ng2 e5 $132) (12. Qe1 $5 {is more or less the same as Qd1-e2, as confirmed by} Nd7 ({no better are} 12... Rfe8 13. Ne5) ({and} 12... Qf4 13. g3) 13. Qe3 {with a direct transposition}) 12... Rfe8 $5 {Interfering the Qe2-e3 plan and getting prepared for e6-e5 at an appropriate point.} ({Imprecise is} 12... Rab8 {because of} 13. Qe2 $1 Rfe8 14. Qe3 Qc7 15. Ne5 $14 {Sadykov - Goryachkina, Titled Tuesday 25th Jan, blitz, 2022}) 13. Qb3 (13. Qe2 $2 {is bad, as it is running into the break} e5) (13. Qb1 {does not leave Black with a choice, regarding the control over the key e5-height, namely} Bxf3 $5 14. Nxf3 e5 15. dxe5 Nxe5 16. Nxe5 Rxe5 17. Rxe5 Qxe5 18. Qe1 {and now:} Qe6 $5 {is a trendy reaction -} (18... Qxe1+ 19. Rxe1 Kf8 20. Kf1 Re8 21. Rxe8+ Kxe8 22. Ke2 Ke7 23. Ke3 Kd6 24. Kd4 (24. g4 h6 25. f4 g5 26. Bf1 Ng8 27. c4 Ne7 28. fxg5 hxg5 29. cxd5 Ke5 30. d6 Kxd6 31. Kd4 a5 32. Bd3 Nc6+ 33. Ke4 Ne7 34. Kd4 Nc6+ 35. Ke4 Ne7 {1/2-1/2 H. Tikkanen - A. Smith, SWE-ch, Ronneby, 2018}) 24... Nd7 25. Bxh7 ({only} 25. c4 dxc4 26. Bxc4 {can preserve White's hopes for more}) 25... g6 26. Bg8 Ne5 27. f4 Nc6+) 19. Qd2 (19. Qxe6 fxe6 20. Re1 Kf7 21. f4 h6 22. g3 g5 $132) 19... Re8 $132 20. a4 g6 21. a5 Qe5 22. Bf1 Kg7 $11) (13. Qc2 Rac8 14. a3 {Now Black has to decide whether to follow the abovementioned plan and push e6-e5 immediately or to make some useful preparatory moves} Qb8 $5 {A subtle waiting move, bringing the b7-b5 option back on the map.} (14... a6 $5 15. Re3 (15. Ne5 $4 {is blundering a key pawn -} Nxd4) 15... Bxf3 $5 16. Nxf3 e5 17. dxe5 Nxe5 18. Nxe5 Rxe5 19. Qd2 Rxe3 20. Qxe3 Re8 $132) (14... Bxf3 {is possible, but there is really no need for Black to rush.} 15. Nxf3 e5 16. dxe5 Nxe5 17. Nxe5 Rxe5 18. Qa4 $5 Rxe1+ 19. Rxe1 $14 {/=}) 15. Qb1 (15. Rac1 b5 $5 16. Qb1 Bxf3 17. Nxf3 Na5 $132) ({in case of} 15. Qb3 {Black can already play} Nd7 16. a4 Qc7 $132) (15. Re3 b5 $132) 15... Bxf3 $1 {(nipping the intended jump to the center into the bud)} 16. Nxf3 e5 17. dxe5 Nxe5 18. Nxe5 Rxe5 19. Rxe5 Qxe5 20. Qe1 Qe6 $1 $11) (13. g4 Bg6 14. Bxg6 hxg6 15. Ne5 Nd7 $132 (15... Nh7 $5 $132)) 13... Qc7 {White's problem is that it's hard to find a proper square for the queen.} 14. Qc2 (14. a4 a6 15. Qa3 Rab8 16. a5 Bxf3 $5 17. Nxf3 g6 18. Re3 Kg7 $132) (14. Ne5 Nxe5 15. Rxe5 Rab8 16. a4 Bg6 $132) 14... Rac8 15. a3 a6 $5 {Black is preparing for simplifications via e5 in a proper moment} 16. Rac1 Bxf3 $5 17. Nxf3 e5 18. dxe5 Nxe5 19. Nxe5 Rxe5 20. Rxe5 Qxe5 21. Rd1 g6 22. Qe2 Qe6 $1 {A typical idea in many lines.} 23. Re1 Re8 $11 *

