{[%evp 0,44,17,18,80,75,62,48,32,19,27,23,46,61,39,11,29,13,12,28,3,11,11,18,10,31,19,19,54,-3,1,28,121,130,118,22,10,37,7,30,27,0,24,36,42,0,26]} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nf6 5. c3 Bg4 6. Qb3 Qc7 {Here White has a choice whether to play in a more positional manner or complicate matters.} 7. h3 (7. Ne2 Bxe2 $5 ({instead, after} 7... Nc6 8. Bf4 Qd7 9. O-O e6 10. Ng3 {the problem with the light-squared bishop remains and} Nh5 {is more or less obligatory -} 11. Nxh5 Bxh5 12. Nd2 Bg6 13. Bxg6 hxg6 14. Rfe1 $14 {/=}) 8. Bxe2 (8. Bf4 $4 {fails to} Qxf4 9. Qxb7 Bg4 $19) 8... e6 9. O-O ({White can start with} 9. Nd2 {, when} Bd6 10. Nf3 O-O 11. O-O Nc6 12. Bd3 Ne4 13. g3 {may transpose}) 9... Bd6 10. g3 Nc6 11. Nd2 O-O 12. Nf3 {White would rely on the pair of bishops, but the problem is that Be2 and his queen are currently misplaced.} (12. Bd3 e5 $132) 12... Ne4 $5 13. Bd3 (13. Ng5 Nf6 $5 14. Bd3 e5 $132) 13... f5 14. Ne1 h6 15. Ng2 g5 $5 16. f3 Nf6 $132) 7... Bh5 $5 {An introduction to a pawn sacrifice.} ({With} 7... Bd7 {I won a very good game against Ganguly in 2020 by introducing the plan} 8. Nf3 e6 9. O-O Bd6 10. Re1 Bc6 {, but here White can pose some problems. Still, I believe it is perfectly playable, but now my preference goes to the more straightforward approach.}) 8. g4 (8. Ne2 {is once again the main alternative, when} Nc6 $1 {appears to be the better choice.} ({Noteworthy, the h3-pawn has taken the g4-square from the bishop and after} 8... Bxe2 $6 {White can already confidently strike with} 9. Bf4 $1) 9. Bf4 (9. g4 Bg6 10. Bxg6 hxg6 11. g5 Nd7 ({worth checking is} 11... Ng8 $5) 12. Qxd5 e5 13. Be3 {is a possible transposition to the leading text}) 9... Qd7 10. Nd2 e6 {Black has lost one tempo by playing Qc7-d7, but Ne2 is slightly misplaced on e2 and this is more important for the general verdict.} 11. Ng1 (11. Bg3 Bd6 12. Nf4 Qc7 $5 13. Nxh5 Nxh5 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 $132) (11. O-O Bd6 12. Bxd6 Qxd6 13. Ng3 Bg6 14. Bxg6 hxg6 15. Nf3 Rb8 $132) 11... Bd6 12. Bxd6 Qxd6 13. Ngf3 O-O 14. O-O Qc7 $132) 8... Bg6 9. Bxg6 hxg6 10. g5 Nfd7 11. Qxd5 e5 12. Ne2 $1 (12. Nf3 {is natural, but in fact, this knight is more vulnerable on that square.} Nc6 13. Be3 O-O-O 14. Qxf7 $6 (14. Nbd2 exd4 15. Nxd4 Nc5 $44) 14... exd4 15. Nxd4 {Shuvalova - Keymer, Juniors Speed Qual, blitz, 2021} (15. cxd4 $2 Bb4+ 16. Ke2 Rhf8 17. Qe6 Rde8 $19) {and Black's initiative grows quickly after} 15... Nce5 $1 16. Qe6 Bc5 17. Nd2 Rhe8 18. Qb3 Nd3+ 19. Ke2 Bb6 $40) 12... Nc6 13. Be3 Nb6 {Now White is at an important crossroads - all the three possible retreats along the big diagonal are more or less equally good:} (13... O-O-O $2 14. Qxf7 exd4 15. cxd4) 14. Qe4 {The most logical and principled reply in my view, since here Black is more limited in his choices in comparison to the other lines:} (14. Qf3 {is an essential alternative:} O-O-O (14... Rd8 $5 {Once again this idea seems to work and give decent compensation, e.g.} 15. Nd2 Be7 {and now:} 16. h4 (16. Qg3 Nd5 17. h4 Qc8 $5 $44) (16. Ne4 exd4 17. Bxd4 (17. Nxd4 Rh4 $1 18. O-O-O Ne5 19. Nb5 Qb8 20. Qg2 Nd3+ 21. Kc2 Qe5 22. Bxb6 axb6 23. Rxd3 Rxd3 $44) (17. cxd4 Rh4 $44) 17... Rh4 {(Black's key resource in all the lines!)} 18. Bxg7 (18. O-O-O Kf8 $44) 18... Ne5 $44) 16... Nd5 $1 17. Ne4 (17. O-O-O Nxe3 18. fxe3 exd4 19. exd4 Nxd4 20. Nxd4 Rxd4 $132) 17... Qa5 $1 18. Kf1 Qb5 $44) (14... Nc4 {is probably a bit premature in the view of} 15. d5 Ne7 16. b3 $14) {is the main continuation -} 15. Nd2 Kb8 $1 ({In this move order Black has to hide the king at first, as confirmed by} 15... Nd5 $6 16. O-O-O exd4 17. Nxd4 Nxe3 18. fxe3 $14 {and Black has to fight for a draw after} Nxd4 19. exd4 Rxd4 20. Rhf1 Rd7 21. Ne4 Rxd1+ 22. Qxd1 Rxh3 23. Qg4+ Qd7 24. Qxd7+ Kxd7 25. Rxf7+ Be7 26. Rxg7) 16. Ne4 (16. h4 Nd5 {arrives at the next crossroads:} 17. O-O-O (17. Nb3 a5 $1 18. O-O-O a4 19. Nd2 a3 $36) (17. Qg3 Bd6 $5 18. Ne4 $1 exd4 (18... Rhe8 $5 $44) 19. Nxd6 dxe3 20. Nxf7 exf2+ 21. Kf1 $1 Ne3+ $1 22. Kxf2 Rhf8 $1 23. Qxc7+ Kxc7 24. Kxe3 Rxf7 25. Nd4 Re7+ 26. Kd3 Red7 $11) 17... Nxe3 18. fxe3 exd4 19. exd4 Nxd4 20. Nxd4 Rxd4 21. Rhf1 Rd7 $132) 16... f5 $1 (16... Nd5 $2 17. O-O-O $16) 17. gxf6 gxf6 {From a human point of view White's position looks quite vulnerable, but the engines are still relatively optimistic about his prospects, e.g.} 18. O-O-O (18. Nxf6 Qf7 $1 19. Bg5 Ka8 $5 $36) (18. Qxf6 Bg7 19. Qf3 exd4 20. cxd4 Bxd4 $44) 18... f5 19. Ng5 (19. Nc5 Bxc5 20. dxc5 Nc4 $132) 19... Nc4 $1 {The key move, otherwise White is just in time to stabilize his position:} 20. Ne6 (20. Kb1 e4 21. Qg3 Bd6 22. Bf4 Qb6 $1 23. b3 N6a5 $1 24. Kc2 Qa6 $1 25. Ra1 Ka8 $5 26. bxc4 Nxc4 $44 {With such an exposed king a repetition is a very likely outcome}) (20. b3 f4 $1 21. bxc4 ({perhaps reconciling himself with a draw after} 21. Bxf4 Qa5 22. bxc4 Qxa2 $5 23. c5 $1 {is White's most reasonable decision -} Bxc5 $5 24. dxc5 Qa1+ $11) 21... fxe3 22. fxe3 $6 Ba3+ 23. Kc2 Qa5 $1 24. Rb1 Qa4+ 25. Rb3 Be7 $5 26. Ne6 (26. Ne4 Qxa2+ 27. Rb2 Qa4+ $17) 26... Qxa2+ 27. Rb2 Nb4+ $1 28. cxb4 Qxc4+ 29. Kb1 Qxe6 $17) 20... Qb6 21. b3 {Now Black can consider two options - in both cases he can objectively claim enough compensation for the pawn:} Nxe3 (21... Ba3+ $5 22. Kb1 Nxe3 23. Qxe3 (23. fxe3 Rde8 24. Ng5 a6 $44) 23... Rde8 24. d5 (24. Nc5 Qc7 $44) 24... Qxe3 25. fxe3 Nd8 {From a strategical point of view Black has a very good compensation, White's only chance is to try to trap the bishop -} 26. Nxd8 (26. Ng5 Bc5 27. e4 Be3 28. h4 Bxg5 29. hxg5 f4 $44) 26... Rxd8 27. b4 a5 $1 28. Kc2 axb4 29. Kb3 Rh4 $1 30. d6 $1 Re4 $1 31. Rd3 b5 $1 $13) 22. Nxd8 (22. fxe3 Ba3+ {transposes to the aforementioned} 23. Kb1 Rde8 $44) 22... Nxd4 $1 23. Rxd4 ({a very exciting line is} 23. Nxd4 Ba3+ 24. Kb1 Nxd1 25. Nf7 Nxc3+ $5 26. Qxc3 Rc8 {with approximate equality after} 27. Nxe5 $1 Rxc3 28. Nd7+ Kc7 29. Nxb6 Kxb6 $11) 23... exd4 24. Nxd4 (24. Nf7 Ba3+ 25. Kb1 dxc3 26. Qxe3 c2+ 27. Kxc2 Rc8+ 28. Nc3 Qxe3 29. fxe3 Bb4 $11) (24. fxe3 Qxd8 25. Nxd4 Qc7 26. Kb2 Bg7 27. Rg1 Rc8 $44) 24... Qxd8 25. Qg3+ (25. fxe3 Qc7 $44) 25... Ka8 26. fxe3 Qa5 (26... Qe8 $5) 27. Kb1 Be7 $1 (27... Ba3 28. e4 $5 fxe4 $2 29. b4 $16) 28. Rc1 Ba3 29. b4 Qd5 $44) (14. Qg2 O-O-O $5 ({It looks to me that this is the most principled one, but there are other options, which deserve to be analyzed in detail, such as} 14... Nc4 $5 15. Nd2 Nxb2 16. Rb1 Nd3+ 17. Kf1 $132) (14... Rd8 $5 15. Nd2 Be7 16. h4 Nd5 $44) 15. Nd2 Kb8 $1 (15... Nd5 16. O-O-O $14) 16. dxe5 (16. h4 Nd5 $44) 16... Nxe5 17. O-O-O Nd3+ $1 (17... Na4 $2 18. Ne4 $16) 18. Kb1 (18. Kc2 Na4 19. b3 Nb4+ 20. Kb1 Nxc3+ $15) 18... Na4 $1 {The first player should not enter such position without any preparation.} 19. b3 $1 Nab2 (19... Nxc3+ $6 20. Nxc3 Qxc3 21. Nc4 $1 $36) 20. Rdg1 (20. Rdf1 Bc5 $44 21. Bxc5 Nxc5 $5 (21... Qxc5 $5) 22. Nd4 (22. Nf3 Rhe8 23. Nfd4 Rxe2 24. Nxe2 Rd2 25. Nd4 Nbd3 26. Qg3 Qxg3 27. fxg3 Ne4 28. Nb5 a6 29. Re1) 22... Nbd3 $44) 20... Bc5 21. Bxc5 (21. Nd4 Bxd4 $5 22. Bxd4 Rxd4 23. cxd4 Qc3 24. Ne4 {[#] Here I was really happy to find an incredibly beautiful draw like} Nc4 $3 25. Nxc3 Na3+ 26. Ka1 Nc2+ $11) 21... Nxc5 (21... Qxc5 $6 22. Ne4 Qa3 {looks crushing, but White is able to cover all the weak points with the help of} 23. Nc1 $1 f5 $140 24. gxf6 gxf6 25. Qxg6 Ne5 26. Qxf6 Nbd3 27. Nxd3 Nxd3 28. c4) 22. Nf3 (22. Nd4 Nbd3 23. Nc4 a6 $5 $44) 22... Rhe8 23. Nfd4 Rxe2 $5 24. Nxe2 Rd2 {and Black reaches by force a balanced endgame -} 25. Nd4 (25. Nc1 Nc4 $1 26. Qh2 $1 Na3+ 27. Ka1 Nc2+ $11) 25... Nbd3 26. Qg3 $1 (26. Qd5 a6 $1 27. Rd1 Rb2+ 28. Ka1 Qa5 29. b4 Qa3 30. Rxd3 Nxd3 31. Qd8+ Ka7 32. Nc6+ $1 $11) 26... Qxg3 $1 27. fxg3 Ne4 $1 28. Nb5 $1 a6 29. Re1 $1 Ndf2 30. Rxe4 Nxe4 31. Re1 f5 (31... axb5 $5 32. Rxe4 Rd3 33. Rg4 Rxc3 34. Kb2 Rf3 $11) 32. gxf6 Nxf6 {, finally restoring the material after} 33. Nd4 Rd3 $11) (14. Qb3 $6 O-O-O 15. Nd2 exd4 16. Bxd4 (16. Nxd4 $6 Nxd4 17. Bxd4 Bc5 18. Bxc5 $2 Rhe8+ 19. Be3 Rxe3+ 20. fxe3 Qg3+ 21. Kd1 Qg2 $19) 16... Nxd4 17. cxd4 Kb8 $40) 14... O-O-O $1 ({Here the e-pawn is pinned and} 14... Rd8 $2 {is apparently falling to} 15. f4 $16) 15. Nd2 f5 $1 {Black must urgently prove compensation.} ({Too slow is} 15... Kb8 $2 16. O-O-O $14 {Black does not simply have time for prophylactic moves.}) 16. gxf6 gxf6 17. dxe5 ({An essential branch is} 17. Qxg6 exd4 {(opening again the e-file) and now:} 18. Nxd4 (18. Bxd4 Nxd4 19. Nxd4 Kb8 $5 {Right now, when the opponent cannot castle, this humble retreat is the best way to prepare for the continuation of the attack, as shown by:} 20. N2b3 (20. Ne4 Rxd4 $1 21. cxd4 Bb4+ 22. Nc3 $1 (22. Kd1 Qc4 $40) 22... Bxc3+ 23. bxc3 Qxc3+ 24. Ke2 Qc4+ 25. Kf3 $1 Rg8 $1 26. Qe4 $1 Qc3+ $1 27. Ke2 Qc4+ $11) (20. Qd3 Bc5 21. N2b3 Bxd4 22. Nxd4 Rhe8+ 23. Kd1 Nd5 $44) 20... Bh6 {There is no safe haven for White's king anymore and he practically does need computer assistance to defend.} 21. Kd1 $1 Nd5 $1 22. Re1 $1 Nf4 23. Qxf6 Qc4 $1 $44 24. Nd2 (24. Qf5 Rhf8 25. Qh7 Nd3 26. Qxb7+ Kxb7) 24... Qa4+ 25. N2b3 Qc4 $11) (18. cxd4 Nd5 19. O-O-O $5 (19. Rc1 Kb8 20. a3 Qd7 21. Qg3+ Ka8 $44) 19... Nxd4+ 20. Kb1 Nxe3 21. fxe3 Nxe2 22. Qg4+ Qd7 23. Qxe2 Rxh3 $11) 18... Nxd4 19. Bxd4 (19. cxd4 $6 Kb8 $36) 19... Bh6 $1 {Yet another very important move - Black has to keep the enemy king in the center at any cost:} 20. Ne4 (20. Be3 Bxe3 21. fxe3 Nd5 22. O-O-O $1 Nxe3 $1 23. Rde1 Qd6 24. Nc4 (24. Re2 Rhg8 25. Qe4 Rge8 $44) 24... Nxc4 25. Qg4+ Kb8 26. Qxc4 Rxh3 $1 $11) (20. Qxf6 $2 {is asking for trouble -} Rhe8+ 21. Kd1 Bxd2 22. Kxd2 Rxd4+ $1 23. cxd4 Nc4+ 24. Kd3 (24. Kc3 Ne3+) 24... Nxb2+ 25. Kd2 Qa5+ 26. Kc2 Re2+ 27. Kb1 Nc4 $1 28. Qf8+ Kd7 $1 29. Qf7+ Kd6 30. Qf8+ Re7 31. Qf4+ Kd7 32. Kc2 Re2+ 33. Kd3 Rd2+ 34. Ke4 Nd6+ 35. Kf3 Qd5+ 36. Kg3 Rxd4 $19 {A picturesque domination!}) 20... Rhe8 21. Kd1 $1 Qc6 (21... Re6 $5) (21... f5 $5) {Once again White's position is quite dangerous, though the computer is able to hold it - here are some sample lines:} 22. Re1 Nc4 23. b3 (23. Kc2 Qb5 24. b3 Na3+ 25. Kb2 Nc4+ $11) 23... Ne5 24. Qf5+ (24. Qxh6 Nf3 25. Re3 Nxd4 26. cxd4 Rxd4+ 27. Nd2 Red8 28. Re2 {with inevitable repetition after} Qh1+ 29. Re1 Qf3+ 30. Kc2 Qf5+ $11) 24... Re6 $5 25. Nc5 Qxc5 26. Qxe6+ Kc7 $1 27. Rxe5 fxe5 28. Qxh6 exd4 29. Qf4+ Kc8 $132) 17... f5 $1 18. Qg2 (18. Qc2 Nb4 $132) 18... Nxe5 19. O-O-O Bc5 $1 {Energetic and strong!} 20. Nf4 (20. Bxc5 Nd3+ {can spell danger only for White, as witnessed by} 21. Kb1 Qxc5 22. Nd4 Rxd4 23. cxd4 Qxd4 24. Rc1+ $1 Nxc1 25. Rxc1+ Kb8 26. Qg3+ Ka8 $132) 20... Bxe3 21. fxe3 Rhe8 22. Nb3 ({Black has sufficient compensation after} 22. Rhe1 Qf7 23. Kb1 Rd7 24. Nb3 g5 $1 $132) ({and} 22. Kb1 Rd6 23. Nb3 Nbc4 $44 {as well.}) 22... Nbc4 $44 *

