{[%evp 0,36,31,18,77,77,80,36,36,36,29,42,43,31,27,36,41,34,31,31,36,27,56,19,33,38,86,51,60,26,25,19,23,15,23,35,41,0,54]} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Nxf6+ exf6 6. c3 Bd6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Ne2 Re8 9. O-O Nd7 {We are going to have a look at specific positions, in which Qc2 and h5 are not inserted.} 10. Ng3 {This ambitious move has the right to exist in the new situation.} (10. Qc2 {is not consistent, since Black is just in time for the comfortable reply} Nf8 $1 11. Ng3 Qc7 12. Bd2 Bd7 $132 {Abdusattorov - Hammer, Titled Tuesday 2nd Febr, 2019.}) (10. Bf4 {A logical way to continue the mobilization, though the trade of the dark-squared bishops is not so advantageous as it looks at first sight.} Nf8 {and now:} 11. Bxd6 (11. Qd2 {White can hardly do without this move, it delays the exchange for a while:} Bxf4 $5 (11... Be6 $5 12. Rfe1 Ng6 13. Bxd6 Qxd6 14. Ng3 {I. Nepomniachtchi - R. Svane, Wch blitz, Warsaw, 2021, can be answered with} Re7 $5 {Rae8:} 15. Ne4 (15. Nf5 Bxf5 16. Bxf5 Rae8 17. Rxe7 (17. Bxg6 hxg6 18. Rxe7 Qxe7 19. Kf1 Qd6 $132) 17... Nxe7 18. Re1 g6 19. Bc2 Rd8 20. Qh6 Kh8 $5 21. Qe3 Nd5 $132) 15... Qd5 16. Nc5 {took place in Garifullina - Gunina, RUS-ch (Women), Moscow, 2020. As seen, Black is ready to trade his Be6, so} Rae8 17. Nxe6 $140 (17. Bf1 h5 $132) 17... Rxe6 18. Rxe6 Rxe6 19. b3 (19. g3 f5 $5 20. Qg5 Rf6 $132) 19... Nh4 20. Bf1 g5 $5 $132) 12. Nxf4 ({in case of} 12. Qxf4 Ne6 13. Qg3 g6 14. Rfe1 {Black has the clever regrouping} Ng7 15. Nf4 Bf5 $132 {with solid position}) 12... Qd6 13. Rfe1 {and now:} Bg4 $5 {This attractive small operation for exchanging yet another minor piece is entirely to my liking.} (13... Bd7 {A conventional reply, Black is opposing along the e-file:} 14. Bf1 {, as in Pingin - Pridorozhni, Satka Autumn, 2023, can be met by} (14. Ne2 g6 15. Ng3 {is too time-consuming, e.g.} Kg7 16. Ne4 (16. h4 Ne6 17. Ne4 Qc7 $132) 16... Qd5 $5 17. b3 Bf5 $132) 14... Ng6 $5 15. Nxg6 (15. Ne2 Rad8 16. Rad1 Be6 $132) 15... hxg6 16. h4 Rxe1 17. Rxe1 Be6 18. a3 b5 $132 {with firm blockade on the light squares}) 14. h3 (14. Bc4 Ng6 $132) 14... Ne6 $1 {(the point!)} 15. Nxe6 (15. Ne2 Bxe2 16. Bxe2 g6 $132) 15... Bxe6 16. Re4 g6 17. Rae1 Kg7 18. h4 h5 19. Bc4 Bd7 20. Rxe8 Rxe8 21. Rxe8 Bxe8 22. g3 {It is essential to learn that this endgame is also equal, for the pawn majority is usually compensated by the better shelter of Black's king, e.g.} Bd7 23. Bf1 Qd5 24. b3 Qf5 25. Bd3 Qa5 $5 $132) 11... Qxd6 {resembles the positions from above. Here various lines, in which White is doing without Ne2-f4, will be the subject of our interest:} 12. Ng3 (12. Qd2 g6 $5 {Black has many decent options, but, generally speaking, I like mostly this plan with f6-f5 coming next:} 13. h4 (13. a4 a5 14. Rfe1 (14. Qh6 Bf5 $5) 14... Kg7 15. Qf4 Rd8 $132) (13. f4 f5 14. g4 $5 {is too harsh, Black can take the challenge -} fxg4 (14... Qe7 $5) 15. f5 {and repel the initiative by preparing a trade of the queens with} Qe7 $1 $132) (13. Qh6 {is once again allowing} Bf5 $1 {- a motif, which is worth remembering!}) 13... h5 14. Rfe1 Kg7 15. Ng3 Be6 16. Ne4 Qd8 17. Qf4 (17. Nc5 b6 $132) 17... Bf5 18. Bc4 $5 Ne6 19. Bxe6 (19. Qg3 Bxe4 20. Rxe4 Nc7 21. Rxe8 Nxe8 22. Re1 Nd6 23. Bb3 Qd7 $132) 19... Rxe6 $132 20. Ng3 (20. Nc5 Rxe1+ 21. Rxe1 b6 22. Ne4 Be6 $132) 20... Rxe1+ 21. Rxe1 Be6 22. b3 b6 $5 {Covering the c5-square, in this typical position Black has enough counterplay -} 23. Ne4 Qe7 24. c4 Rd8 $5 $132 (24... Bxc4 25. bxc4 f5 26. Qd6 Re8 $11)) 12... g6 $5 13. Ne4 (13. Qd2 {can occur via 12.Qd2 as well, after} Kg7 14. Rfe1 Be6 15. h4 h5 {the game transposes to the variation from above}) 13... Qd8 14. Re1 Kg7 15. Qf3 {So far Ochsner - Thybo, DEN-ch, Svendborg, 2018, after} Bf5 $5 ({in case of} 15... f5 16. Nc5 {White retains some pressure, while Bc8 looks passive}) 16. h4 h5 {Black has a decent position -} 17. Re3 Bxe4 18. Rxe4 Ne6 19. Re3 Nc7 $132) (10. Be3 Nf8 11. Ng3 g6 $5 12. Ne4 Be7 $132) (10. a4 a5 {does not change much.}) 10... g6 $5 {I have deliberately chosen this one among many equally good continuations, for it contains the characteristic plan of building a solid pawn chain.} 11. Bh6 $1 {White's main try.} (11. Ne4 Bf8 12. Bf4 {is only a temporary achievement, for these minor pieces will be pretty soon pushed back, as shown by} Nb6 13. Re1 Nd5 14. Bd2 f5 15. Ng5 Rxe1+ 16. Qxe1 h6 17. Nf3 Be6 18. Qc1 (18. c4 Nf6 19. b3 Bg7 20. Bc3 a5 $132) 18... Kh7 19. c4 Nf6 20. Qc2 Ne4 $132) (11. Qf3 {does not discourage} f5 $1 12. Ne2 Nf6 13. Bg5 Be7 $132) 11... f5 12. Qd2 (12. Bxf5 $4 gxf5 13. Nxf5 {is effortlessly refuted by} Nf8 $19) 12... Bf8 13. Bg5 {Keeping these bishops on the board is the best way to proceed.} (13. Bxf8 Nxf8 14. Ne2 Be6 15. Rfe1 Qd6 $132) ({Black succeeds in covering everything after the preliminary} 13. Rae1 {as well, for example} Nf6 14. Bxf8 Rxf8 15. Qg5 (15. h4 Be6 16. h5 Bxa2 $132) 15... Ng4 (15... Kg7 $5 16. Nxf5+ Bxf5 17. Bxf5 c5 $1 $11) 16. Qf4 Be6 17. h3 Nf6 18. Re5 Kg7 19. Rfe1 Re8 (19... Nd5 20. Qd2 Qh4 21. c4 Nf6 {Vaishali - Gukesh, IND, Juniors qual, 2020} 22. Ne2 $14) 20. c4 a5 21. b3 a4 22. b4 a3 $132) (13. h4 Bxh6 14. Qxh6 Nf6 15. Rfe1 Be6 $132) 13... Nf6 ({A serious tactical omission is} 13... Be7 $2 14. Bxe7 Rxe7 15. Bxf5 $1 $16) 14. h4 $5 (14. Rfe1 {is a natural follow-up, which sets a crafty trap:} Rxe1+ {is a necessary insertion, as shown by} ({in a blitz game I forgot my line and played immediately} 14... Be6 {, which is not a bad mistake yet - after} 15. d5 $5 (15. h4 $5) {the only move is} 15... Bd7 $1 (15... cxd5 $4 {is dropping material after} 16. Bb5 $18 {tteshan (2510) - eljanov (2791) Live Chess Chess.com, 2023}) 16. Rxe8 Bxe8 {and, according to the engines, Black can hold, but his position is precarious}) 15. Rxe1 Be6 16. h4 (16. a3 Bg7 $132) 16... a5 $5 ({a plausible alternative, based on play on the light squares, is} 16... b5 $5 17. h5 Be7 18. Bc2 a5 $132) 17. a4 (17. h5 a4 $132) 17... h5 18. Ne2 Bb3 $1 $132 19. Bxf5 $5 {An interesting piece sacrifice, which is enough only for a draw with correct play.} (19. Ra1 Qd6 $132) 19... gxf5 20. Ng3 {and here} Qd6 $1 {is the safest reply, for example} 21. Bf4 $1 $11 Qd7 ({the game can also end in a repetition after} 21... Qd8 22. Bg5) 22. Bh6 Bxh6 23. Qxh6 Re8 24. Qg5+ Kf8 $1 ({safer than} 24... Kh7 25. Rc1) 25. Qh6+ Kg8 $11) 14... Be7 $5 15. Rfe1 Be6 16. h5 (16. Re2 Nd5 17. Rae1 b5 $5 $132) 16... Nd5 17. Bxe7 Rxe7 {Black has managed to mobilize and position is double-edged.} 18. c4 (18. Qg5 $6 Re8 $15) (18. Re5 Re8 19. Rae1 Qh4 20. Bc4 Nc7 $1 $132) (18. Bc4 Nc7 $132) 18... Nc7 $132 *

