{[%evp 0,38,25,25,56,57,70,21,40,36,32,43,35,17,9,25,27,23,29,29,35,23,36,31,28,13,51,28,24,16,44,48,52,35,35,56,69,2,54,45,31]} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Nxf6+ exf6 6. c3 Bd6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Qc2 Re8+ 9. Ne2 h5 $5 {This trendy continuation is Black's most sound and ambitious option. It is now up to the first player to choose where to castle.} (9... h6 10. O-O {looks like a better version for White of lines with castling to the short.}) 10. Be3 {The more active location of this bishop is once again intending to support the pawn center after c3-c4, as well as White is ready to castle to the long.} (10. Bd2 {is more correlated to the plan with castling to the short. Here curious is} c5 $5 ({besides the normal development} 10... Nd7 11. O-O-O Nf8 {, which is also fine, Black can challenge the more restrained development of Bc1 by the ambitious textmove}) 11. O-O-O (11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. O-O Nc6 13. Nf4 Ne5 $132) (11. O-O Nc6 12. Rfe1 Bg4 $5 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. b4 Bb6 $132) 11... Nc6 12. Be3 {Kyc - Rudzinska, EU-ch Rapid, Katowice, 2022} (12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. Nf4 Ne5 14. Bb5 Bd7 $132) 12... Qa5 $5 13. dxc5 (13. Kb1 $6 cxd4 14. Nxd4 Nxd4 15. Bxd4 Bg4 16. f3 Be6 $36) 13... Bxc5 14. Bxc5 Qxc5 15. Nf4 h4 $5 16. Kb1 Kf8 $5 17. f3 Bd7 $132) 10... Nd7 11. O-O-O (11. Ng3 {is an ambitious move, but Black can objectively solve the opening problems due to some tactical intricacies, starting with} Nb6 $1 {, when the path diverges:} 12. O-O-O (12. Nxh5 Nd5 $36 13. O-O (13. O-O-O $2 {fails to} Bg4 $1 14. Be2 Bxe2 15. Qxe2 g6 16. Ng3 f5 $19) 13... Bg4 14. Ng3 Nxe3 15. fxe3 Bxg3 16. hxg3 Rxe3 $132) (12. O-O Nd5 (12... h4 $5 13. Ne4) 13. Bd2 (13. Nxh5 Bg4 {reaches the line from above}) 13... h4 14. Ne4 Nf4 $5 {(indeed,, there are various plausible alternatives to this jump)} 15. Nxd6 Qxd6 16. Rfe1 Bd7 17. Bf1 h3 $5 18. g3 Ng6 19. Qd3 Rxe1 20. Rxe1 Be6 $132) 12... Nd5 13. Bd2 Nf4 14. Bxf4 Bxf4+ 15. Kb1 Qd5 $1 16. Be4 {1/ 2-1/2 Manish - Krstulovic, Budapest Vezerkepzo, 2021,} ({no better is} 16. c4 Qxg2 17. Nxh5 Qf3 $1 $15) {Black can fight for the maximum by means of} 16... Qg5 $1 17. Bd3 Bg4 18. f3 Be6 $15) (11. c4 {is possible, but it is hardly of independent significance after} Nf8 12. O-O-O {etc.}) 11... Nf8 12. Kb1 {A flexible prophylactic move, White can also consider:} (12. h3 Be6 13. c4 (13. g4 $6 Bd5 14. Rhg1 h4 15. c4 Bf3 $15) 13... b5 $1 {A typical strike:} 14. c5 (14. d5 $2 cxd5 15. c5 Qa5 $1 ({the tactical justification of Black's idea rather than} 15... Rc8 16. Bxb5 {Concio - Daneshvar, Titled Tuesday 11th Jan, 2022}) 16. a3 Rac8 17. Kb1 b4 $15) 14... Bc7 15. Kb1 (15. g4 h4 16. Rhg1) 15... a5 16. g4 Bd5 17. Rhg1 h4 $1 {would have been the right decision - Black must prefer to keep the g-file closed than being tempted by material gain. His chances are not worse after} (17... Bh2 18. gxh5 Bxg1 (18... Bf3 $5 {deserves serious attention, while the textmove wins an exchange, but it gives White a free-hand on the kingside}) 19. Rxg1 Kh8 {was in Bharath - Eljanov, Titled Tuesday 12th Jan, 2021,} 20. Bh6 $1 g5 21. hxg6 $16) 18. Nc3 (18. g5 b4 19. Rg4 a4 20. gxf6 Qxf6 21. Rdg1 Ne6 $36) 18... Bf3 19. Be2 Bxe2 20. Nxe2 b4 21. g5 Ng6 22. gxf6 Qxf6 23. d5 cxd5 24. Rxd5 Qc6 $5 $132) (12. Nf4 $6 {is an instructive mistake because of} Bxf4 $1 13. Bxf4 Be6 14. Kb1 b5 $1 15. h3 a5 16. g4 $6 Qd5 $17 {M. Golubev - R. Svane, Titled Tuesday 4th Aug, 2020}) (12. Ng3 g6 13. Ne4 {is a better idea, but Black was able to show his cards by} Be7 14. c4 f5 15. Nc3 Bg5 $1 $132 {, when} 16. Rhe1 $6 {in Terletsky - Mikhailovsky, Titled Tuesday 4th Aug, 2020} (16. Qd2 $142 Bxe3 17. fxe3 Be6 $132) {could be penalized by} 16... Rxe3 $1 17. fxe3 Qxd4 18. Kb1 Qe5 $17 {with huge compensation for the exchange}) ({In reply to} 12. c4 {Black's continuation in the leading text} h4 $5 {does also work:} 13. h3 (13. a3 Bg4 14. Kb1 {is likely to transpose to 13.h3, see below}) (13. Rhg1 Bg4 $1 14. Bf5 Bxf5 $5 15. Qxf5 Qc8 16. Qxc8 Raxc8 17. g3 c5 $5 18. d5 (18. b3 b5 $1 $132) 18... Ng6 $132) 13... Be6 14. Kb1 {has a similar course to the popular line with 12...Be6, which is mentioned below, but the additional moves with the h-pawns seem to provide Black with extra opportunities, for example} Rc8 {and now:} 15. Nc3 (15. a3 Ng6 $1 ({a refinement of} 15... g6 16. Nc3 f5 {Yoo - Duda, Julius Baer GenCup, rapid, 2022,} 17. Rhe1 a6 18. Qd2 $14) 16. Rhe1 a6 $5 17. Bc1 b5 18. c5 Bc7 $132) 15... Ng6 $1 {The same manoeuvre has proved effective again.} 16. a3 Ne7 17. Rhe1 g6 18. Bc1 Nf5 19. Be4 $5 ({an attempt at establishing a piece control over the key d5-square in anticipation of the imminent central break in comparison to the known practical example} 19. Re4 Bf8 20. d5 cxd5 21. cxd5 Bd7 $132 {S. Fedorchuk - A. Petrossian, Aix en Provence, 2022}) 19... Bb8 $5 20. d5 cxd5 21. Bxd5 ({Black has his resources after} 21. Nxd5 Be5 $1 $132 {, so is in the text}) 21... Bxd5 22. Rxe8+ Qxe8 23. Nxd5 Kg7 $132) 12... h4 $5 {I have decided to recommend this rare move because it contains an interesting concept - Black's idea is to put the bishop on g4 and either move it to g6 via h5 or to trade it for Ne2 in an appropriate moment.} ({The main line with} 12... Be6 {is quite normal in my opinion, e.g.} 13. Bc1 Qa5 14. c4 b5 15. Bd2) 13. c4 {The consequent move, besides, White has several interesting set-ups like:} (13. Bc1 $5 Bg4 ({opening the g-file against the own king by} 13... h3 $6 {is less to the point}) 14. f3 (14. h3 Bh5 15. g4 hxg3 16. fxg3 Qe7 17. Rde1 Bg6 18. Nf4 Bxd3 19. Nxd3 Qd7 $132) (14. Rhg1 Bh5 15. Rde1 (15. f4 f5 $132) 15... Qc7 16. g3 Bf3 $132) 14... Bh5 15. Rdf1 $1 ({White has rich play for the pawn after} 15. d5 $5 cxd5 16. Nd4 {, so it is worth giving it back in search of a counterplay -} Qb6 17. g4 Bg6 18. Nf5 d4 19. cxd4 Ne6 $132) 15... Bg6 16. g3 Bxd3 17. Qxd3 Ng6 {White is dreaming about attack, but Black is well mobilized and ready to strike at the center, e.g.} 18. Rhg1 ({both} 18. f4 Qe7 19. Rf2 Qe4 20. Qxe4 Rxe4 21. gxh4 Rae8 22. Ng3 Re1 $132) ({and} 18. gxh4 Nxh4 19. Ng3 Qa5 20. Rhg1 Re6 $132 {are double-edged, as well as in the text}) 18... Qe7 (18... Qa5 19. f4 f5 20. c4 $14) 19. Rf2 Qe6 20. gxh4 $140 Nxh4 21. Ng3 Bf8 22. Nh5 Kh8 $132) (13. h3 Be6 14. Rhg1 (14. c4 {transposes to the 12.c4-line, see above}) 14... Bh2 15. Rh1 Bd6 $11) (13. Rhg1 $5 {An inspiring idea to prepare an advance of the g2-pawn and, as we will see, it is also connected with a sound exchange sacrifice.} Bg4 14. h3 Bh5 15. g4 $1 hxg3 (15... Bg6 16. Bf5 $14) 16. Nxg3 Bxg3 17. Rxg3 Bxd1 18. Qxd1 {looks very temping, but after} Ne6 $1 {Black is ready to evacuate Kg8 with sufficient counterplay, e.g.} 19. f4 (19. Qh5 $6 Kf8 $1 20. c4 Qd6 $15) (19. h4 Kf8 20. h5 Ng5 $5 $132) 19... Kf8 $1 20. f5 (20. Qg4 Qd5 21. f5 Ng5 22. Bxg5 fxg5 23. Qxg5 Re1+ 24. Kc2 Qxa2 25. Kd2 $1 Qa1 26. Qxg7+ Ke7 27. Be2 $1 Rxe2+ $5 $11) 20... Ng5 21. Qg1 Qd5 22. h4 Nf3 (22... Ne4 23. Rxg7 Nd6 $132) 23. c4 Qe4 $3 {A fantastic intermediate move!} 24. Bxe4 Nxg1 25. Bd3 Rxe3 26. Rxe3 Re8 $132) 13... Bg4 $5 14. a3 {The way to get rid of the annoying pin of Ne2 by stopping the possible Bd6-b4.} (14. h3 Bh5 15. a3 Rb8 $5 {just transposes}) (14. Rd2 Qc7 $5 (14... Bb4 $5) 15. h3 (15. c5 Bxh2) 15... Bxe2 16. Rxe2 Bf4 $132) 14... Rb8 $5 {Preparing b7-b5.} 15. h3 (15. Rd2 h3 $1 16. gxh3 Bf3 17. Rc1 b5 $1 $132) 15... Bh5 16. Rd2 (16. Rc1 Ng6 17. Rhe1 b5 $132) 16... Ng6 17. Rc1 (17. c5 Bc7 18. Rg1 Ne7 $132) 17... b5 $5 {The intended thrust is coming just in time.} 18. d5 (18. cxb5 cxb5 19. Qb3 Bxe2 $1 20. Bxe2 Qd7 $132) (18. c5 Bc7 $15) 18... bxc4 19. Bxc4 c5 $5 $13 {In this complex position it seems to me that in the long run Black's play is easier due to the safer king.} *

