{[%evp 0,54,33,11,57,70,67,35,35,35,37,37,37,27,23,23,21,29,29,14,35,33,41,41,33,42,25,28,22,11,17,13,69,53,53,64,80,80,58,61,56,-8,-1,15,15,22,0,0,0,-7,19,21,20,0,7,24,37]} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Nxf6+ exf6 6. c3 Bd6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Qc2 Re8+ 9. Ne2 h5 10. O-O h4 11. h3 (11. Bf4 Na6 $1 {White's last move has hindered 11...Nd7, so this is the only way to bring the knight into play at once. As in many similar cases, Black is not afraid to get doubled pawns.} 12. h3 (12. Qd2 Nc7 13. Rfe1 Bxf4 {leaves White with a choice:} 14. Qxf4 (14. Nxf4 g5 $1 {A brave and very sound attempt to enhance the development and initiate play on the dark squares, as demonstrated by:} 15. Nh5 (15. Ne2 Bg4 $1 16. h3 (16. f3 Bh5 $132) 16... Bxe2 17. Rxe2 Qd6 18. Bc2 Kg7 19. Rxe8 Rxe8 20. Qd3 Rh8 21. Re1 Ne6 22. Qf5 Nf4 $132) 15... Bg4 16. Rxe8+ Nxe8 17. Be2 Bxh5 18. Bxh5 Nd6 19. f4 (19. Re1 Qa5 $132) 19... Qa5 $1 20. Rf1 Kg7 $132) 14... g5 $1 15. Qf3 Kg7 {is similar -} 16. Bc2 Be6 17. b3 Nd5 18. c4 Ne7 $132) (12. Bxd6 Qxd6 13. Bxa6 (13. h3 Nc7 14. Rfe1 Bd7 {is more or less balanced:} 15. c4 (15. Bh7+ Kh8 16. Bf5 g6 17. Bxd7 Qxd7 18. Nf4 Kg7 19. Nd3 {, as in S. Ali - A. Salem, Sharjah Blitz, 2022, looks sensible, but Black has the strong reaction} Qf5 $1 20. Rad1 ({White can hardly benefit from further simplifications, for instance} 20. Rxe8 Rxe8 21. Re1 $2 Rxe1+ 22. Nxe1 Qe6 $17) 20... a5 21. a4 b5 $15) 15... Rad8 16. Rad1 b5 $5 17. b3 (17. c5 Qd5 $132) 17... bxc4 18. bxc4 Ne6 $132) 13... bxa6 14. h3 Bf5 $5 (14... a5 $132) 15. Qd2 a5 16. Rae1 {took place in Nepomniachtchi - Alonso Rosell, Julius Baer rapid, 2023, when Black could have played} Rab8 $5 17. Nc1 a4 18. Rxe8+ Rxe8 19. Re1 Rxe1+ 20. Qxe1 a3 $132) (12. Rfe1 Nc7 13. Qd2 {- 12.Qd2}) 12... Nc7 13. Qd2 Nd5 (13... Bxf4 $6 {is ill-timed when the rook is still on f1, for instance} 14. Qxf4 g5 15. Qd2 $16 {[%cal Yf2f4]}) 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. Rfe1 {is yet another key position:} Ne7 $1 {This move can be considered a novelty in spite of the fact I have already tried it in some online blitz games. Black wishes to spare a tempo on Bd7 and occupy the important f5-square and this idea has been approved by the existing examples:} (15... Bd7 {can also occur via 12.Qd2, the practice has seen} 16. Rad1 a5 $6 (16... Ne7 $5) 17. c4 Ne7 18. Nc3 $14 {1/2-1/ 2 A. Horvath - P. Prohaszka, HUN-ch Rapid Ajka, 2022}) 16. Qf4 (16. Rad1 Bf5 17. Qf4 (17. Nc1 g6) 17... Qd5 $5 (17... Qxf4 18. Nxf4 Bd7 $5 $132) 18. c4 Qa5 19. b4 Qa4 $1 20. Nc3 Qxb4 $132) (16. Nf4 Bd7 (16... g6 {is possible, the over-optimistic} 17. Nh5 $2 gxh5 18. Qh6 {was refuted exactly by} Bf5 19. Bc4 Nd5 20. Qxh5 $140 Qf4 $1 21. Bb3 Bg6 $19 {and Black won convincingly after} 22. Qd1 Rxe1+ 23. Qxe1 Kf8 24. c4 Re8 25. Qa5 Re2 26. Rf1 Ne3 {LdEbom0231 (2831)- eljanov (2870), Live Chess Chess.com, 2023}) 17. c4 g6 {and now:} 18. Rad1 (18. Bc2 Rad8 19. c5 Qc7 20. b4 (20. Nxg6 $4 {is a blunder -} Nxg6 21. Qc3 Kg7 $19 {0-1 LdEbom0231 (2902)-eljanov (2874) Live Chess Chess.com 2023}) 20... Kg7 $132) 18... Kg7 $132) (16. c4 Bf5 $132 {(the mentioned point of Black's move order!)} 17. Rad1 g6 $5 (17... Rad8 $5 18. b3 g6 19. Bxf5 Nxf5 20. d5 cxd5 21. cxd5 Kg7 $15 {1/2-1/2 LdEbom0231 (2920)-eljanov (2856) Live Chess Chess.com 2023}) 18. Qf4 (18. Qh6 $6 {is just a loss of time -} Bxd3 19. Rxd3 Nf5 20. Qd2 {0-1 LdEbom0231 (2885)-eljanov (2891) Live Chess Chess.com 2023} Rad8 $15) 18... Qxf4 19. Nxf4 Bxd3 20. Rxd3 {1/2-1/2 LdEbom0231 (2893)-eljanov (2883) Live Chess Chess.com 2023} Rad8 21. Kf1 Kf8 $132) 16... Qxf4 17. Nxf4 Kf8 18. g3 hxg3 19. fxg3 Rd8 20. Re2 Nd5 $132) (11. Nf4 {is a tricky option, though objectively not a dangerous one -} Nd7 12. Qd1 $5 {The critical continuation - White is trying to launch a kingside attack.} ({instead,} 12. h3 Nf8 {is likely to transpose to a subline of the leading text, see below}) 12... Bxf4 $5 {is an original concrete solution, e.g.} (12... Nf8 $5 {is reliable, even though Black has to show some precision -} 13. Qh5 Qc7 (13... Bxf4 $5) 14. g3 Qd7 $1 {This subtle manoeuvre solves all the problems.} 15. Ng2 (15. Bd2 Bxf4 16. Bxf4 g5 $1 17. Bd2 Qh3 18. Qf3 Kg7 $132 {Blohberger - Palozza, Bassano del Grappa, 2020}) 15... hxg3 16. hxg3 Qg4 ({both consequent and the safest option, Black can also try} 16... c5 $5) 17. Qxg4 (17. Qh2 $5 Qf3 $5 18. Ne3 f5 $132) 17... Bxg4 18. Bf4 {Nasuta - Sadhwani, Titled Tuesday 15th Sept, 2020, and here} Bxf4 19. Nxf4 g6 20. Rfe1 Ne6 21. Ng2 Kg7 $132) 13. Bxf4 h3 $1 14. Qh5 ({White might suffer on light squares for long after} 14. g3 $6 Nf8 15. f3 Ng6 16. Qd2 Be6 $36) 14... Nf8 15. gxh3 (15. g4 c5 $132) 15... Be6 16. Rfe1 Qd7 17. Bf1 b5 $5 18. a4 a6 $44) ({White can try to save a tempo on h2-h3 by} 11. Bd2 {, but soon or later White will be forced to play it, e.g.} Nd7 ({this useful manoeuvre makes more sense than the impatient} 11... h3 12. Ng3 $1) 12. Rae1 (12. Rfe1 Nf8) 12... Nf8 13. h3 ({a necessity; in reply to} 13. Nf4 {Black can already switch to the familiar light-squared strategy by means of} Bxf4 $1 14. Bxf4 h3 $36)) 11... Nd7 12. Bd2 ({Since the main plan for White here is connected with the f2-f4 thrust, it is not in its spirit to play} 12. Be3 {, for example} Nf8 13. c4 (13. Rad1 Be6 14. c4 {is the same}) 13... Be6 14. Rad1 Rc8 $1 {A multifunctional move - Black prepares both b7-b5 and the battery Bb8-Qc7 at an appropriate moment.} 15. Rfe1 Bb8 {and now:} 16. b3 (16. Bf4 Bxf4 17. Nxf4 g6 $1 18. Be4 Qd6 19. Qc1 Bxc4 $5 20. Nxg6 fxg6 ({worth checking is} 20... Bd5 $5 $132 {- after the forced} 21. Bxd5 {Black cannot probably saddle the opponent with an isolated pawn for long, for instance} Rxe1+ 22. Rxe1 Nxg6 23. Bb3 Kg7 $140 24. d5 Rc7 25. dxc6 Rxc6 26. Qe3 Qe5 $1 27. Rd1 Qxb2 28. Qxa7 Rc1 29. Rxc1 Qxc1+ 30. Kh2 Qf4+ $11) 21. Qxc4+ Kg7 22. d5 cxd5 23. Qxd5 Qxd5 24. Bxd5 b6 $11 {1/2-1/2 Quparadze - Mahdavi, Yerevan, 2023}) (16. Nf4 b5 $1 17. c5 Qc7 $132) 16... b5 {has been tested in practice -} 17. Kf1 (17. Bf4 bxc4 18. bxc4 Bxf4 19. Nxf4 g6 $132) 17... bxc4 18. bxc4 Ng6 19. Ng1 Qd7 $132 {H. Celik - G. Dudin, Podgorica, 2021.}) 12... Nf8 13. Rae1 $1 {The logical follow-up.} ({More restrained is} 13. Rfe1 Be6 (13... Bc7 $5) 14. Rad1 Qd7 15. Nf4 g6 $132) 13... Bc7 14. f4 $1 {The point! White needs to hurry, for Black is about to obtain full control on the kingside by means of building the pawn chain g6-f5, as shown by:} (14. Nf4 Be6 $1 15. Nxe6 Nxe6 {is a kind of critical position:} 16. Bh7+ ({If} 16. Qd1 g6 $1 17. Qg4 {, then after} Qd6 18. f4 Kg7 19. Rf3 (19. Qxh4 $2 Nxd4 $17) 19... c5 $1 {White's position looks vulnerable and he has to take urgent measures like} 20. Kf1 $1 cxd4 $140 21. f5 Ng5 22. Rxe8 Rxe8 23. fxg6 fxg6 24. cxd4 Bb6 $5 $132 (24... Nxf3 25. Qxg6+ Kf8 26. Bb4 $1 Qxb4 27. Qxf6+ $11)) (16. f4 c5 $5 $132) 16... Kf8 $5 17. Bf5 Qd6 18. f4 Ng5 $1 (18... Kg8 $5) 19. Qd1 g6 20. Bc2 f5 ({following the general plan, which can instantly lead to a perpetual; besides, Black has also} 20... Ne6 $5 $132 {at his disposal}) 21. Rxe8+ Rxe8 22. fxg5 Qh2+ 23. Kf2 Qg3+ {1/ 2-1/2 A. Sileika - J. Ragnarsson, EU-ch 2020 pr13, ICCF email.}) (14. c4 {is met by} Ne6 $1 (14... g6 {is premature because of} 15. d5 $1 $36) 15. Be3 g6 $1 16. c5 Ng7 $36) (14. b3 {A mysterious move, which has been tried twice by Sjugirov.} g6 (14... Ne6 $5 15. f4 Qd6 $132 {Tekeyev - Esipenko, RUS-ch Higher League, Yaroslavl, 2018}) 15. Kh1 {So far Sjugirov - Bai Jinshi, CHN-RUS Summit, Qinhuangdao, 2018, when White intends to reroute his knight to f3, but} b5 $5 16. Ng1 Rxe1 17. Rxe1 Be6 18. Nf3 Qd7 $1 $132 {seems to be an antidote.}) 14... Qd6 $5 {A rare, but quite playable line.} (14... g6 {is more popular and probably not that bad. But position after} 15. f5 {(by the textmove Black would like to exclude this possibility)} g5 16. c4 (16. Qd1 $5) 16... b6 17. g3 $5 (17. b4 a5 18. bxa5 {Vocaturo - Di Nicolantonio, FRA-chT Top 16 GpB, Chartres, 2022} Qd6 $5) 17... hxg3 18. Be4 {looks precarious, for example} Qd7 19. Qd3 {etc.}) 15. c4 $1 (15. Kh1 {is less consistent, for instance} b5 $5 16. b3 Rb8 17. c4 bxc4 18. bxc4 f5 $132) 15... f5 $5 $146 {A sound pawn sacrifice, Black will have the d4- and f4-pawns as targets in return.} ({Black does not succeed in putting an own pawn on the f5-square after} 15... g6 $6 {because of the intermediate push} 16. c5 $1 Qd7 {and now} 17. f5 $16) ({The textmove is an improvement upon} 15... Ne6 16. Kh1 b6 17. d5 cxd5 18. cxd5 Nc5 19. Nc3 Bd7 {, as in Alinasab - Salimova, Olympiad Women-44, Chennai, 2022, when White stays on top by means of} 20. Bh7+ Kf8 21. b4 Na6 22. a3 $16) 16. Bxf5 Bxf5 17. Qxf5 Re6 $1 {The most principled way to proceed.} ({In case of} 17... Re7 18. c5 $14 {Qd6, unlike in the leading text, will be lacking the d7-square.}) ({However, it seems that} 17... Nh7 $5 {is a decent alternative, e.g.} 18. Qg4 Bd8 $1 19. Bc3 Bf6 $44 {with ample Black's compensation for the pawn.}) 18. d5 ({After} 18. c5 Qd7 19. d5 cxd5 20. Nd4 Rxe1 21. Bxe1 Re8 $5 22. Bxh4 Ne6 {White's position looks overextended and it is hard to believe that he can fight for any advantage, for example} 23. Nxe6 (23. Re1 g6 $1 {kicks Qf5 away from the d5-pawn and the material will be again even after} 24. Qg4 Nxc5 $11) (23. b4 Qa4 $1 $132) 23... Rxe6 24. Bf2 b6 25. b4 d4 $44 26. Rd1 $4 Re1+ $19) ({The preliminary} 18. Qd3 Rae8 {before} 19. c5 Qd7 {is of little use -} 20. f5 Re4 $132) 18... Ree8 ({Black can insert} 18... cxd5 $5 19. cxd5 $140 Ree8 20. Nc3 Qb6+ 21. Kh1 Qxb2 22. Qd3 Qa3 $1 $132) 19. Kh1 {A clever idea to avoid the possible checks.} ({After} 19. Nc3 Qc5+ 20. Kh1 Qxc4 $132 {Black regains the pawn with interest.}) (19. b4 {is a plausible alternative, to which necessary is} a5 $1 {(it is important to open the a-file)} 20. a3 axb4 21. axb4 (21. Bxb4 {allows} Bb6+ 22. Kh1 Bc5 $132) 21... cxd5 22. c5 Qg6 $132) 19... cxd5 20. Nc3 $5 ({Rather than this curious pawn sacrifice it is possible to take the central one -} 20. Qxd5 {and precision is required from Black, for example} Qxd5 21. cxd5 Ng6 22. Nc3 (22. f5 Ne7 {will transpose}) 22... Ne7 $1 23. f5 (23. Rf3 Nf5 $44) 23... Bg3 $1 24. Re4 f6 $1 25. Rf3 Rad8 26. Be3 (26. Rfe3 $6 Kf7 $15) 26... Kf7 $132 {, calmly preparing to get rid of the d5-pawn. The eventual loss of a7-pawn should not seriously bother Black, for the enemy king is in a cage.}) 20... dxc4 21. Nd5 Bb6 22. Bc3 (22. Bb4 {is neutralized by the only, but sufficient} Qg6 $1 $11 {, based on the small tactical operation} 23. Ne7+ $4 Rxe7 24. Qxg6 $140 Rxe1 $1 $19) 22... Qg6 $1 {Once again this is the most accurate move, after which Black should easily repel the initiative in the ensuing queenless endgame.} 23. Qxg6 fxg6 24. Nxb6 axb6 25. Rxe8 Rxe8 26. f5 gxf5 27. Rxf5 Nd7 $1 {The precise route for the knight - the double b-pawns are still needing protection.} 28. Rg5 Re7 29. Rg4 Nc5 (29... b5 30. Rg5 Nb6 31. Rxb5 Na4 {is another way to initiate counterplay of his own.}) 30. Rxc4 Re4 ({Alternatively,} 30... Ne4 {aims at exchanging the bishop, when the rook ending is holdable even if White emerges with a single extra pawn on the queenside.}) 31. Rd4 Rxd4 32. Bxd4 {and here Black can force matters by} Nd3 $5 ({Instead,} 32... Kf7 $11 {is insisting on keeping the material balance.}) 33. Bxb6 Nxb2 34. Bd8 b5 35. Bxh4 Nd3 36. a3 ({Or} 36. g4 b4 37. Bg5 Nc5 $44 {/= and the inevitable 38....b3 will clear the queenside as well.}) 36... b4 37. axb4 Nxb4 $11 {with the same outcome.} *

